{"title_page": "DAKS", "text_new": "{{short description|British luxury fashion house}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name        = DAKS Simpson Group plc\n|logo        = DAKS company logo.jpg\n|foundation  = [[City of London]], England (1894)\n|founder     = Simeon Simpson\n|key_people  = Paul Dimond (deputy chairman)<br>\n{{nowrap|Luigi Veccia (creative director)}}\n|owner       = [[Sankyo Seiko Co., Ltd.|Sankyo Seiko Co. Limited]] (since 1991)\n|hq_location = London, UK<br>Japan\n|industry    = Fashion\n|products    = Clothing<br>[[Fashion accessory|Accessories]]\n|homepage    = {{url|www.daks.com}}\n}}\n[[File:DAKS Old Bond Street.JPG|thumb|DAKS flagship store on 10 Old Bond Street]]\n[[File:DAKS catwalk image.jpg|thumb|Looks from DAKS' SS13 shows]]\n'''DAKS''' is a British luxury [[fashion house]], founded in 1894 by Simeon Simpson in [[London]]. The name is a combination of the initials of '''A'''lexander '''S'''impson and an initial and final letter of his business associate '''D'''udley Bec'''k'''.\n\nDAKS holds [[Royal Warrant of Appointment (United Kingdom)|royal warrants]] granted from three members of the [[British Royal Family|Royal Family]], one of 15 firms (out of 820) to do so. Officially granted to DAKS' Simpson Piccadilly store in 1956 was the royal warrant of [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|HRH The Duke of Edinburgh]], followed by that of HM [[Elizabeth II|The Queen]] in 1962 and HRH [[Charles, Prince of Wales|The Prince of Wales]] in 1982.\n\nWorldwide, DAKS is exported to 30 countries and sold in over 2,000 specialty shops, major stores and concessions. Since 1991 the company is owned by [[Sankyo Seiko Co., Ltd.|Sankyo Seiko Co. Limited]].<ref>{{in lang|ja}} [http://www.sankyoseiko.co.jp/brand/daks.html DAKS] sankyoseiko.co.jp </ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early years \u2013 S Simpson===\n\nIn 1894 Simeon Simpson, aged 16, rented a room on Middlesex Street, [[East London]], with the intention of setting up a business in [[bespoke tailoring]], focused on high standard craftsmanship.<ref name=\"daks_a\">{{cite web|url = http://www.daks.com/products/tailoring/the-story.aspx|title = The Story|date = December 2012|accessdate = 27 December 2012}}</ref> Several innovations of technology at the time were being introduced with [[machinery]] capable of making buttonholes and electric powered saws to cut many layers of fabric at once \u2013 Simpson saw the potential for such equipment for producing garments in higher quantities while still upholding quality tailoring techniques, aiming to improve [[ready-to-wear]] standards as no male or female professionals considered ready-to-wear for suitable attire at the time.<ref name=wain>{{cite book |last= Wainwright |first= David |authorlink=  |title= The British Tradition: Simpson \u2013 A World of Style |url= |year=1996 |publisher=Quiller Press Ltd |location=London |isbn= 1-899163-158 |page= |pages=}}</ref>{{rp|2}} Simpson's methods proved successful in speeding up the process and he set up several factories within London, which soon required expansion in its early years through popularity of the label.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|1-2}}\n\nAlexander Simpson, his second son, joined the business aged 15 in 1917, and by 1929 had planned and opened a larger factory in Stoke Newington where production could be centralised, this again had to be enlarged a few years later.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|3}}\n\n===20th century \u2013 DAKS and Simpsons Piccadilly===\n\nWith the continued growth of the company Alexander Simpson began to take more control of the business, and in 1935 DAKS tailored the first self-supporting trouser.<ref name=\"daks\">{{cite web|url = https://daks.com/pages/ourhistory|title = Our History - DAKS|accessdate = 10 April 2020|}}</ref> The trousers were available in many colours and fabrics that weren't generally associated with menswear.  Soon after a DAKS womenswear line was released, using the patented waistband for skirting.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|52}}\n\nAt the turn of the 21st century when the company was acquired by Japanese group Sankyo Seiko Co. Limited in 1991, the S Simpson name was dropped and DAKS became the new brand name.<ref>http://www.fashionmodeldirectory.com/brands/daks/</ref>\n\nThe ease-of-wear of the trousers and how they allowed movement, as intended from Simpson's invention, led to DAKS being popular in sporting wear \u2013 kitting tennis, golf, motor racing, and football players, and even for the British Olympic team in 1960.<ref name=\"daks_a\" /> The company was commissioned by the British Government at the time of the [[Second World War]] to produce military [[uniform]]s for officers in the Army, Navy, Royal Airforce and Women's Services<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daks.com/products/tailoring/the-story.aspx |title=The Story |publisher=Daks.com |accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> even despite the semi-destruction of the Stoke Newington factory due to bomb damage and loss of electricity<ref name=wain/>{{rp|54}}\n\u2013 with about seven million garments made for military services being produced.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|58}}\n\nAfter the war when DAKS clothes were announced to start selling to the public again queues of people would form down Piccadilly, to which Simpson tailors would measure them in line and present suitable pairs of trousers to them when they got into the [[Simpsons of Piccadilly]] store.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|58}}\n\n====Simpsons of Piccadilly====\n[[File:Simpsons of Piccadilly 2005.jpg|thumb|Simpsons of Piccadilly]]\n{{Main|Simpsons of Piccadilly}}\nSimeon Simpson's son Alexander Simpson founded [[Simpsons of Piccadilly]].<ref name=wain /> The new building was designed by architect [[Joseph Emberton]] as a new and revolutionary retail establishment,<ref name=wain/>{{rp|28}} the shop front windows exhibited the first curved glass display in Great Britain and the largest in the world at the time,<ref name=wain/>{{rp|17}} these were designed so that no reflection would be cast to obscure the displays inside. The store opened in April 1936 by Sir [[Malcolm Campbell]], the world-famous [[motor-racing]] driver.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|25}} and was known for its visual merchandising and window displays by [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Moholy-Nagy]], a former director from the Bauhaus school.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bauhaus-online.de/en/atlas/personen/laszlo-moholy-nagy|title=Laszlo Moholy-Nagy|publisher=Bauhaus-Online|date=28 November 2012}} Retrieved 27 December 2012</ref> Alexander Simpson died the following year of [[leukaemia]] aged just 34.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|37}}\n\nSimpsons continued to trade in the Simpsons Piccadilly building for several decades more, helping officers and civilians during [[World War II]],<ref name=wain/>{{rp|53}} and in later years branched out to sell other clothing by designer labels such as [[Armani]] and [[Christian Dior]]<ref name=wain/>{{rp|123-124}} Since 1999 Simpsons stopped trading at the Piccadilly store and moved the renamed DAKS to a new [[flagship]] store and London offices to [[Old Bond Street]],<ref>[http://shoponline.daks.com/About-DAKS/History.aspx DAKS website \u2013 history] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501074315/http://shoponline.daks.com/About-DAKS/History.aspx |date=1 May 2012 }} Retrieved 27 December 2012</ref> whilst moving to another new store on [[Jermyn Street]] which was refurbished in 2012 to focus on selling classic menswear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2012-10/08/daks-new-mens-store-jermyn-street-london|title=Checking out London's new Daks store|date=October 2012|access-date=27 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012010912/http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2012-10/08/daks-new-mens-store-jermyn-street-london|archive-date=12 October 2012|url-status=dead}} Retrieved 27 December 2012</ref> The original store was sold to bookseller [[Waterstone's]] and now serves as their flagship store.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/264230.stm|title=Real 'Grace Bros' Store Closes|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=1 February 1999}} Retrieved 27 December 2012</ref>\n\n==Royal Warrants and House Check==\n\n[[HRH]] [[The Duke of Edinburgh]] visited the company's [[Larkhall]] factory in [[Scotland]] in recognition of its role in exporting goods worldwide.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|75}}\n\n(Larkhall was built in 1948 to Simpson's specifications and was opened by [[Harold Wilson]] who later became Prime Minister of the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"number10\">[http://www.number10.gov.uk/past-prime-ministers/harold-wilson/ Number 10]. Retrieved 27 December 2012</ref> The factory since closed in the early 2000s<ref name=\"number10\" />). DAKS was granted the [[Royal Warrant of Appointment (United Kingdom)|Royal Warrant]] of Appointment by [[HRH]] [[The Duke of Edinburgh]] in 1956. Her Majesty [[Elizabeth II|The Queen]] and [[HRH The Prince of Wales]] granted the company with Royal Warrants in 1962 and 1982 respectively.\n\nThe company developed a House Check in 1976 by Johnny Mengers, the Group managing director of the time and last family chairman.<ref name=\"telegraph\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1397579/John-Mengers.html/ Telegraph]. Retrieved 27 December 2012</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Savile Row tailoring]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|DAKS}}\n* {{official website|http://www.daks.com}}\n\n{{British Royal Warrant holders}}\n\n[[Category:Clothing companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1856]]\n[[Category:Youth culture in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British brands]]\n[[Category:High fashion brands]]\n[[Category:Luxury brands]]\n[[Category:Clothing brands of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Royal Warrant holders]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British luxury fashion house}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name        = DAKS Simpson Group plc\n|logo        = DAKS company logo.jpg\n|foundation  = [[City of London]], England (1894)\n|founder     = Simeon Simpson\n|key_people  = Paul Dimond (deputy chairman)<br>\n{{nowrap|Luigi Veccia (creative director)}}\n|owner       = [[Sankyo |Sankyo Seiko Co. Limited]] (since 1991)\n|hq_location = London, UK<br>Japan\n|industry    = Fashion\n|products    = Clothing<br>[[Fashion accessory|Accessories]]\n|homepage    = {{url|www.daks.com}}\n}}\n[[File:DAKS Old Bond Street.JPG|thumb|DAKS flagship store on 10 Old Bond Street]]\n[[File:DAKS catwalk image.jpg|thumb|Looks from DAKS' SS13 shows]]\n'''DAKS''' is a British luxury [[fashion house]], founded in 1894 by Simeon Simpson in [[London]]. The name is a combination of the initials of '''A'''lexander '''S'''impson and an initial and final letter of his business associate '''D'''udley Bec'''k'''.\n\nDAKS holds [[Royal Warrant of Appointment (United Kingdom)|royal warrants]] granted from three members of the [[British Royal Family|Royal Family]], one of 15 firms (out of 820) to do so. Officially granted to DAKS' Simpson Piccadilly store in 1956 was the royal warrant of [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|HRH The Duke of Edinburgh]], followed by that of HM [[Elizabeth II|The Queen]] in 1962 and HRH [[Charles, Prince of Wales|The Prince of Wales]] in 1982.\n\nWorldwide, DAKS is exported to 30 countries and sold in over 2,000 specialty shops, major stores and concessions. Since 1991 the company is owned by [[Sankyo |Sankyo Seiko Co. Limited]].<ref>{{in lang|ja}} [http://www.sankyoseiko.co.jp/brand/daks.html DAKS] sankyoseiko.co.jp </ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early years \u2013 S Simpson===\n\nIn 1894 Simeon Simpson, aged 16, rented a room on Middlesex Street, [[East London]], with the intention of setting up a business in [[bespoke tailoring]], focused on high standard craftsmanship.<ref name=\"daks_a\">{{cite web|url = http://www.daks.com/products/tailoring/the-story.aspx|title = The Story|date = December 2012|accessdate = 27 December 2012}}</ref> Several innovations of technology at the time were being introduced with [[machinery]] capable of making buttonholes and electric powered saws to cut many layers of fabric at once \u2013 Simpson saw the potential for such equipment for producing garments in higher quantities while still upholding quality tailoring techniques, aiming to improve [[ready-to-wear]] standards as no male or female professionals considered ready-to-wear for suitable attire at the time.<ref name=wain>{{cite book |last= Wainwright |first= David |authorlink=  |title= The British Tradition: Simpson \u2013 A World of Style |url= |year=1996 |publisher=Quiller Press Ltd |location=London |isbn= 1-899163-158 |page= |pages=}}</ref>{{rp|2}} Simpson's methods proved successful in speeding up the process and he set up several factories within London, which soon required expansion in its early years through popularity of the label.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|1-2}}\n\nAlexander Simpson, his second son, joined the business aged 15 in 1917, and by 1929 had planned and opened a larger factory in Stoke Newington where production could be centralised, this again had to be enlarged a few years later.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|3}}\n\n===20th century \u2013 DAKS and Simpsons Piccadilly===\n\nWith the continued growth of the company Alexander Simpson began to take more control of the business, and in 1935 DAKS tailored the first self-supporting trouser.<ref name=\"daks\">{{cite web|url = https://daks.com/pages/ourhistory|title = Our History - DAKS|accessdate = 10 April 2020|}}</ref> The trousers were available in many colours and fabrics that weren't generally associated with menswear.  Soon after a DAKS womenswear line was released, using the patented waistband for skirting.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|52}}\n\nAt the turn of the 21st century when the company was acquired by Japanese group Sankyo Seiko Co. Limited in 1991, the S Simpson name was dropped and DAKS became the new brand name.<ref>http://www.fashionmodeldirectory.com/brands/daks/</ref>\n\nThe ease-of-wear of the trousers and how they allowed movement, as intended from Simpson's invention, led to DAKS being popular in sporting wear \u2013 kitting tennis, golf, motor racing, and football players, and even for the British Olympic team in 1960.<ref name=\"daks_a\" /> The company was commissioned by the British Government at the time of the [[Second World War]] to produce military [[uniform]]s for officers in the Army, Navy, Royal Airforce and Women's Services<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daks.com/products/tailoring/the-story.aspx |title=The Story |publisher=Daks.com |accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> even despite the semi-destruction of the Stoke Newington factory due to bomb damage and loss of electricity<ref name=wain/>{{rp|54}}\n\u2013 with about seven million garments made for military services being produced.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|58}}\n\nAfter the war when DAKS clothes were announced to start selling to the public again queues of people would form down Piccadilly, to which Simpson tailors would measure them in line and present suitable pairs of trousers to them when they got into the [[Simpsons of Piccadilly]] store.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|58}}\n\n====Simpsons of Piccadilly====\n[[File:Simpsons of Piccadilly 2005.jpg|thumb|Simpsons of Piccadilly]]\n{{Main|Simpsons of Piccadilly}}\nSimeon Simpson's son Alexander Simpson founded [[Simpsons of Piccadilly]].<ref name=wain /> The new building was designed by architect [[Joseph Emberton]] as a new and revolutionary retail establishment,<ref name=wain/>{{rp|28}} the shop front windows exhibited the first curved glass display in Great Britain and the largest in the world at the time,<ref name=wain/>{{rp|17}} these were designed so that no reflection would be cast to obscure the displays inside. The store opened in April 1936 by Sir [[Malcolm Campbell]], the world-famous [[motor-racing]] driver.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|25}} and was known for its visual merchandising and window displays by [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Moholy-Nagy]], a former director from the Bauhaus school.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bauhaus-online.de/en/atlas/personen/laszlo-moholy-nagy|title=Laszlo Moholy-Nagy|publisher=Bauhaus-Online|date=28 November 2012}} Retrieved 27 December 2012</ref> Alexander Simpson died the following year of [[leukaemia]] aged just 34.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|37}}\n\nSimpsons continued to trade in the Simpsons Piccadilly building for several decades more, helping officers and civilians during [[World War II]],<ref name=wain/>{{rp|53}} and in later years branched out to sell other clothing by designer labels such as [[Armani]] and [[Christian Dior]]<ref name=wain/>{{rp|123-124}} Since 1999 Simpsons stopped trading at the Piccadilly store and moved the renamed DAKS to a new [[flagship]] store and London offices to [[Old Bond Street]],<ref>[http://shoponline.daks.com/About-DAKS/History.aspx DAKS website \u2013 history] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501074315/http://shoponline.daks.com/About-DAKS/History.aspx |date=1 May 2012 }} Retrieved 27 December 2012</ref> whilst moving to another new store on [[Jermyn Street]] which was refurbished in 2012 to focus on selling classic menswear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2012-10/08/daks-new-mens-store-jermyn-street-london|title=Checking out London's new Daks store|date=October 2012|access-date=27 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012010912/http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2012-10/08/daks-new-mens-store-jermyn-street-london|archive-date=12 October 2012|url-status=dead}} Retrieved 27 December 2012</ref> The original store was sold to bookseller [[Waterstone's]] and now serves as their flagship store.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/264230.stm|title=Real 'Grace Bros' Store Closes|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=1 February 1999}} Retrieved 27 December 2012</ref>\n\n==Royal Warrants and House Check==\n\n[[HRH]] [[The Duke of Edinburgh]] visited the company's [[Larkhall]] factory in [[Scotland]] in recognition of its role in exporting goods worldwide.<ref name=wain/>{{rp|75}}\n\n(Larkhall was built in 1948 to Simpson's specifications and was opened by [[Harold Wilson]] who later became Prime Minister of the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"number10\">[http://www.number10.gov.uk/past-prime-ministers/harold-wilson/ Number 10]. Retrieved 27 December 2012</ref> The factory since closed in the early 2000s<ref name=\"number10\" />). DAKS was granted the [[Royal Warrant of Appointment (United Kingdom)|Royal Warrant]] of Appointment by [[HRH]] [[The Duke of Edinburgh]] in 1956. Her Majesty [[Elizabeth II|The Queen]] and [[HRH The Prince of Wales]] granted the company with Royal Warrants in 1962 and 1982 respectively.\n\nThe company developed a House Check in 1976 by Johnny Mengers, the Group managing director of the time and last family chairman.<ref name=\"telegraph\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1397579/John-Mengers.html/ Telegraph]. Retrieved 27 December 2012</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Savile Row tailoring]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|DAKS}}\n* {{official website|http://www.daks.com}}\n\n{{British Royal Warrant holders}}\n\n[[Category:Clothing companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1856]]\n[[Category:Youth culture in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British brands]]\n[[Category:High fashion brands]]\n[[Category:Luxury brands]]\n[[Category:Clothing brands of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Royal Warrant holders]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSankyo(link changed toSankyo Seiko Co., Ltd.; link changed toSankyo Seiko Co., Ltd.) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DAKS"}
