{"title_page": "143rd New York Volunteer Infantry", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 143rd Regiment, New York Volunteer Infantry\n|image=\n|dates= August 14, 1862 - July 20, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Infantry]]\n|equipment= \n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles= [[Siege of Suffolk]]<br/>[[Battle of Wauhatchie]]<br/>[[Battle of Missionary Ridge]]<br/>[[Atlanta Campaign]]<br/>[[Battle of Resaca]]<br/>[[Battle of Dallas]]<br/>[[Battle of New Hope Church]]<br/>[[Battle of Allatoona]]<br/>[[Battle of Marietta]]<br/>[[Battle of Kennesaw Mountain]]<br/>[[Battle of Peachtree Creek]]<br/>[[Siege of Atlanta]]<br/>[[Sherman's March to the Sea]]<br/>[[Carolinas Campaign]]<br/>[[Battle of Bentonville]]\n}}\n\nThe '''143rd Regiment, New York Volunteer Infantry''' (a.k.a. \"Sullivan County Regiment\") was an [[infantry]] [[regiment]] in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Service==\nThe 143rd New York Infantry was organized at [[Monticello, New York|Monticello]], [[New York (state)|New York]], beginning August 14, 1862 and mustered in for three years service on October 8, 1862 under the command of [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] David P. DeWitt.\n\nThe regiment was attached to 3rd Brigade, Abercrombie's Division, Defenses of Washington, D.C., to February 1863. 3rd Brigade, Abercrombie's Division, [[XXII Corps (Union Army)|XXII Corps]], [[Department of Washington]], to April 1863. 2nd Brigade, 3rd Division, [[VII Corps (Union Army)|VII Corps]], [[Department of Virginia]], to May 1863. 1st Brigade, 2nd Division, [[IV Corps (Union Army)|IV Corps]], to July, 1863. 1st Brigade, 3rd Division, [[XI Corps (Union Army)|XI Corps]], [[Army of the Potomac]], to October 1863, and [[Army of the Cumberland]] to April 1864. 3rd Brigade, 1st Division, [[XX Corps (Union Army)|XX Corps]], Army of the Cumberland, to July 1865.\n\nThe 143rd New York Infantry mustered out July 20, 1865.\n\n==Detailed service==\n'''1862:'''\n\n14 October: Left New York for Washington, D.C.\n\n'''1863:'''\n\nDuty in the defenses of Washington, D. C. until April.\n\nApril 18: Moved to Suffolk, Va.\n\nApril 20 -- May 4: Siege of Suffolk.\n\nMay 3: Providence Church.\n\nMay 4: Suffolk razed.\n\nJune 24 -- July 7: Dix's Campaign on the Peninsula.\n\nJuly 10: Moved to Washington, D.C.\n\nJuly 13 -- 22: Pursuit of Lee to Berlin, Md.\n\nNear Bristoe Station, Va., until September.\n\nSeptember 24 -- October 3: Movement to Bridgeport, Ala.\n\nOctober 20: Reconnaissance from Bridgeport to Trenton (detachment).\n\nOctober 25 -- 29: March along line of Nashville & Chattanooga Railroad to Lookout Valley, Tenn.\n\nOctober 26 -- 29: Reopening Tennessee River.\n\nOctober 28 -- 29: Battle of Wauhatchie, Tenn.\n\nNovember 23 -- 27: Chattanooga-Ringgold Campaign.\n\nNovember 23: Orchard Knob.\n\nNovember 24 -- 25: Tunnel Hill. \n\nNovember 25: Missionary Ridge.\n\nNovember 28 -- December 17: March to the relief of Knoxville.\n\n'''1864:'''\n\nDuty in Lookout Valley until May.\n\nMay 1 -- 8: Atlanta Campaign.\n\nMay 8 -- 11 Demonstration on Rocky Faced Ridge.\n\nMay 14 -- 15: Battle of Resaca.\n\nMay 19: Near Cassville.\n\nMay 22 -- 25: Advance on Dallas.\n\nMay 25: New Hope Church.\n\nMay 26 -- June 5: Battles about Dallas, New Hope Church, and Allatoona Hills.\n\nJune 4: Ackworth.\n\nJune 10 -- July 2: Operations about Marietta and against Kennesaw.\n\nJune 11 -- 14: Pine Hill.\n\nJune 15 -- 17: Lost Mountain.\n\nJune 15: Gilgal or Golgotha Church.\n\nJune 17: Muddy Creek.\n\nJune 19: Noyes Creek.\n\nJune 22: Kolb's Farm.\n\nJune 27: Assault on Kennesaw.\n\nJuly 4: Ruff's Station or Smyrna Camp Ground.\n\nJuly 5 -- 17: Chattahoochie River.\n\nJuly 19 -- 20: Peachtree Creek.\n\nJuly 22 -- August 25: Siege of Atlanta.\n\nAugust 26 -- September 2: Operations at Chattahoochie River Bridge.\n\nSeptember 2 -- November 15: Occupation of Atlanta.\n\nOctober 26 -- 29: Expedition from Atlanta to Tuckum's Cross Roads.\n\nNovember 15 -- December 10: March to the sea.\n\nDecember 9: Montieth Swamp..\n\nDecember 10 -- 21: Siege of Savannah.\n\n'''1865:'''\n\nJanuary through April: Carolinas Campaign.\n\nMarch 16: Averysboro, N.C.\n\nMarch 19 -- 21: Battle of Bentonville.\n\nMarch 24: Occupation of Goldsboro.\n\nApril 7 -- 13: Advance on Raleigh.\n\nApril 14: Occupation of Raleigh.\n\nApril 26: Bennett's House.\n\nApril 29 -- May 20: Surrender of Johnston and his army. Marched to Washington, D.C., via Richmond, Va.\n\nMay 24: [[Grand Review of the Armies]]\n\nDuty at Washington, D.C., until July.\n\n==Casualties==\nThe regiment lost a total of 220 men during service; 5 officers and 37 enlisted men killed or mortally wounded, 1 officer and 177 enlisted men died of disease.\n\n==Commanders==\n* Colonel David P. DeWitt - discharged April 29, 1863\n* Colonel Horace Boughton\n\n==Notable members==\n* [[Sergeant#American Civil War|Sergeant]] [[Thomas D. Collins]], Company H - [[Medal of Honor]] recipient for action at the Battle of Resaca\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|American Civil War|New York (state)}}\n* [[List of New York Civil War regiments]]\n* [[New York in the Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n* ''143d Regiment New York Vols. Inft., Sullivan Co.'' (Monticello, NY: Watchman Print.), 1892.\n* Dyer, Frederick H. ''A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion'' (Des Moines, IA: Dyer Pub. Co.), 1908.\n* Harris, Robert F. ''The Last Dispatch Rider'' (Bloomington, IN: AuthorHouse), 2009. {{ISBN|1-4389-3499-8}}\n* Sullivan County Civil War Centennial Commission. ''Brass Buttons and Leather Boots: Sullivan County and the Civil War'' (South Fallsburg, NY: Steingart Associates), 1963.\n* Young, Moses G. ''A Condensed History of the 143d Regiment, New York Volunteer Infantry, of the Civil War, 1861-1865'' (Newburgh, NY: Newburgh Journal Print. House), 1909.\n;Attribution\n* {{CWR}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Civil War regiments|Infantry 143]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 143rd New York Volunteer Infantry Regiment\n|image=\n|dates= August 14, 1862 - July 20, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Infantry]]\n|equipment= \n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles= [[Siege of Suffolk]]<br/>[[Battle of Wauhatchie]]<br/>[[Battle of Missionary Ridge]]<br/>[[Atlanta Campaign]]<br/>[[Battle of Resaca]]<br/>[[Battle of Dallas]]<br/>[[Battle of New Hope Church]]<br/>[[Battle of Allatoona]]<br/>[[Battle of Marietta]]<br/>[[Battle of Kennesaw Mountain]]<br/>[[Battle of Peachtree Creek]]<br/>[[Siege of Atlanta]]<br/>[[Sherman's March to the Sea]]<br/>[[Carolinas Campaign]]<br/>[[Battle of Bentonville]]\n}}\n\nThe '''143rd New York Volunteer Infantry''' (a.k.a. \"Sullivan County Regiment\") was an [[infantry]] [[regiment]] in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Service==\nThe 143rd New York Infantry was organized at [[Monticello, New York|Monticello]], [[New York (state)|New York]], beginning August 14, 1862 and mustered in for three years service on October 8, 1862 under the command of [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] David P. DeWitt.\n\nThe regiment was attached to 3rd Brigade, Abercrombie's Division, Defenses of Washington, D.C., to February 1863. 3rd Brigade, Abercrombie's Division, [[XXII Corps (Union Army)|XXII Corps]], [[Department of Washington]], to April 1863. 2nd Brigade, 3rd Division, [[VII Corps (Union Army)|VII Corps]], [[Department of Virginia]], to May 1863. 1st Brigade, 2nd Division, [[IV Corps (Union Army)|IV Corps]], to July, 1863. 1st Brigade, 3rd Division, [[XI Corps (Union Army)|XI Corps]], [[Army of the Potomac]], to October 1863, and [[Army of the Cumberland]] to April 1864. 3rd Brigade, 1st Division, [[XX Corps (Union Army)|XX Corps]], Army of the Cumberland, to July 1865.\n\nThe 143rd New York Infantry mustered out July 20, 1865.\n\n==Detailed service==\n'''1862:'''\n\n14 October: Left New York for Washington, D.C.\n\n'''1863:'''\n\nDuty in the defenses of Washington, D. C. until April.\n\nApril 18: Moved to Suffolk, Va.\n\nApril 20 -- May 4: Siege of Suffolk.\n\nMay 3: Providence Church.\n\nMay 4: Suffolk razed.\n\nJune 24 -- July 7: Dix's Campaign on the Peninsula.\n\nJuly 10: Moved to Washington, D.C.\n\nJuly 13 -- 22: Pursuit of Lee to Berlin, Md.\n\nNear Bristoe Station, Va., until September.\n\nSeptember 24 -- October 3: Movement to Bridgeport, Ala.\n\nOctober 20: Reconnaissance from Bridgeport to Trenton (detachment).\n\nOctober 25 -- 29: March along line of Nashville & Chattanooga Railroad to Lookout Valley, Tenn.\n\nOctober 26 -- 29: Reopening Tennessee River.\n\nOctober 28 -- 29: Battle of Wauhatchie, Tenn.\n\nNovember 23 -- 27: Chattanooga-Ringgold Campaign.\n\nNovember 23: Orchard Knob.\n\nNovember 24 -- 25: Tunnel Hill. \n\nNovember 25: Missionary Ridge.\n\nNovember 28 -- December 17: March to the relief of Knoxville.\n\n'''1864:'''\n\nDuty in Lookout Valley until May.\n\nMay 1 -- 8: Atlanta Campaign.\n\nMay 8 -- 11 Demonstration on Rocky Faced Ridge.\n\nMay 14 -- 15: Battle of Resaca.\n\nMay 19: Near Cassville.\n\nMay 22 -- 25: Advance on Dallas.\n\nMay 25: New Hope Church.\n\nMay 26 -- June 5: Battles about Dallas, New Hope Church, and Allatoona Hills.\n\nJune 4: Ackworth.\n\nJune 10 -- July 2: Operations about Marietta and against Kennesaw.\n\nJune 11 -- 14: Pine Hill.\n\nJune 15 -- 17: Lost Mountain.\n\nJune 15: Gilgal or Golgotha Church.\n\nJune 17: Muddy Creek.\n\nJune 19: Noyes Creek.\n\nJune 22: Kolb's Farm.\n\nJune 27: Assault on Kennesaw.\n\nJuly 4: Ruff's Station or Smyrna Camp Ground.\n\nJuly 5 -- 17: Chattahoochie River.\n\nJuly 19 -- 20: Peachtree Creek.\n\nJuly 22 -- August 25: Siege of Atlanta.\n\nAugust 26 -- September 2: Operations at Chattahoochie River Bridge.\n\nSeptember 2 -- November 15: Occupation of Atlanta.\n\nOctober 26 -- 29: Expedition from Atlanta to Tuckum's Cross Roads.\n\nNovember 15 -- December 10: March to the sea.\n\nDecember 9: Montieth Swamp..\n\nDecember 10 -- 21: Siege of Savannah.\n\n'''1865:'''\n\nJanuary through April: Carolinas Campaign.\n\nMarch 16: Averysboro, N.C.\n\nMarch 19 -- 21: Battle of Bentonville.\n\nMarch 24: Occupation of Goldsboro.\n\nApril 7 -- 13: Advance on Raleigh.\n\nApril 14: Occupation of Raleigh.\n\nApril 26: Bennett's House.\n\nApril 29 -- May 20: Surrender of Johnston and his army. Marched to Washington, D.C., via Richmond, Va.\n\nMay 24: [[Grand Review of the Armies]]\n\nDuty at Washington, D.C., until July.\n\n==Casualties==\nThe regiment lost a total of 220 men during service; 5 officers and 37 enlisted men killed or mortally wounded, 1 officer and 177 enlisted men died of disease.\n\n==Commanders==\n* Colonel David P. DeWitt - discharged April 29, 1863\n* Colonel Horace Boughton\n\n==Notable members==\n* [[Sergeant#American Civil War|Sergeant]] [[Thomas D. Collins]], Company H - [[Medal of Honor]] recipient for action at the Battle of Resaca\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|American Civil War|New York (state)}}\n* [[List of New York Civil War regiments]]\n* [[New York in the Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n* ''143d Regiment New York Vols. Inft., Sullivan Co.'' (Monticello, NY: Watchman Print.), 1892.\n* Dyer, Frederick H. ''A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion'' (Des Moines, IA: Dyer Pub. Co.), 1908.\n* Harris, Robert F. ''The Last Dispatch Rider'' (Bloomington, IN: AuthorHouse), 2009. {{ISBN|1-4389-3499-8}}\n* Sullivan County Civil War Centennial Commission. ''Brass Buttons and Leather Boots: Sullivan County and the Civil War'' (South Fallsburg, NY: Steingart Associates), 1963.\n* Young, Moses G. ''A Condensed History of the 143d Regiment, New York Volunteer Infantry, of the Civil War, 1861-1865'' (Newburgh, NY: Newburgh Journal Print. House), 1909.\n;Attribution\n* {{CWR}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Civil War regiments|Infantry 143]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/143rd_New_York_Volunteer_Infantry"}
{"title_page": "Anton Yelchin", "text_new": "{{short description|American film and television actor}}\n{{Eastern Slavic name|Viktorovich|Yelchin}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Anton Yelchin\n| image              = Anton Yelchin Deauville 2011.jpg\n| caption            = Yelchin in September 2011\n| birth_name        = \u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d \u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0415\u043b\u044c\u0447\u0438\u043d\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1989|03|11}}\n| birth_place        = [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]] (now Saint Petersburg, [[Russia]])\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2016|06|19|1989|03|11}}\n| death_place        = [[Studio City, Los Angeles|Studio City, California]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = Blunt [[traumatic asphyxia]]\n| resting_place      = [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]]\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 2000\u20132016\n| website            = {{URL|antonyelchinfoundation.org}} {{URL|antonyelchinofficial.com}}\n| relatives          = [[Eugene Yelchin]] (uncle)\n}}\n\n'''Anton Viktorovich Yelchin''' ({{lang-rus|\u0410\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d \u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0415\u043b\u044c\u0447\u0438\u043d|p=\u0250n\u02c8ton \u02c8jel\u02b2t\u0255\u026an}}; March 11, 1989 \u2013 June 19, 2016) was an American<!-- Rather than Russian/Russian-born, etc. See [[Wikipedia:Manual of Style (biographies)]] \u2013 \"The opening paragraph should only give: Nationality (In the normal case this will mean the country of which the person is a citizen or national, or was a citizen when the person became notable.\" Also see interview at http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1285/is_3_36/ai_n16123748 \u2013 \"But I don't really think of myself as Russian anymore\u2014I didn't even live there for that long.\" --> actor. He played [[Pavel Chekov]] in three ''[[Star Trek (film series)|Star Trek]]'' films: ''[[Star Trek (film)|Star Trek]]'' (2009), ''[[Star Trek Into Darkness]]'' (2013), and the posthumously released ''[[Star Trek Beyond]]'' (2016). Born to a Russian Jewish family in [[Leningrad]], Yelchin and his family moved to the United States when he was a baby. In the late 1990s, Yelchin began appearing in television and film roles. His role in [[Steven Spielberg]]'s miniseries ''[[Taken (TV miniseries)|Taken]]'' helped further his career.<ref name=\"Ask\" /> Yelchin also starred in ''[[Huff (TV series)|Huff]]'', the films ''[[Fright Night (2011 film)|Fright Night]]'', ''[[Hearts in Atlantis (film)|Hearts in Atlantis]]'', ''[[Alpha Dog]]'', ''[[Like Crazy]]'', ''[[Green Room (film)|Green Room]]'', and the posthumously released ''[[Trollhunters]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nYelchin was born on March 11, 1989, in [[Leningrad]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]] (now Saint Petersburg, [[Russia]]).<ref name=\"guardianobit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2016/jun/20/anton-yelchin-obituary-film-actor|title=Anton Yelchin obituary|last=Gilbey|first=Ryan|date=June 20, 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=UK|accessdate=June 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl/2008_4518258/film-feature-a-beaming-yelchin-is-getting-beamed-u.html|title=A beaming Yelchin is getting beamed up/Young actor, starring as teenager in Charlie Bartlett, sets his sights on the stars|last=Bentley|first=Rick|date=February 22, 2008|publisher=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref> His parents, Irina Korina and Viktor Yelchin, were [[Pair skating|pair figure skaters]] who were stars of the Leningrad Ice Ballet for 15 years.<ref name=\"Yelchinarticle1\">{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1989-12-22/entertainment/ca-920_1_guest-stars|title=Former Soviet Skate Stars Top Bill at Knott's|last=Slate|first=Libby|date=December 22, 1989|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|page=1|quote=Then too there was religious and political oppression. In 1972, as the nationally third-ranked pair team, they qualified for the Olympics but were not permitted to go because of their religion.|accessdate=February 16, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Yelchinarticle2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.pottsmerc.com/article/MP/20090510/ENTERTAINMENT01/305109960|title=A bold step for young actor|last=Longsdorf|first=Amy|date=May 10, 2009|publisher=The Mercury|accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref> His family is [[Jewish]] and were subjected to [[Antisemitism in the Soviet Union|religious and political oppression in the Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"Yelchinarticle1\" /><ref name=\"wanderl\">{{cite news|url=http://trendmag2.trendoffset.com/display_article.php?id=221103|title=The Wanderlust of Anton Yelchin|last=LaGambina|first=Gregg|publisher=Flaunt|year=2009|quote=The Star of David has been in my family for a long time, and obviously I'm Jewish.|accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"jjournal1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/the_ticket/item/anton_yelchin_explores_extramarital_loves_time_slot_in_5_to_7|title=Anton Yelchin explores extramarital love's time slot in '5 to 7'|last=Pfefferman|first=Naomi|date=April 2, 2015|publisher=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]]|accessdate=June 19, 2016}}</ref> Yelchin said that his grandparents \"suffered in ways [he] can't even begin to understand under [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]]\".<ref name=\"jjournal1\" /> Nationally, Yelchin's parents were the third-ranked pair team; they thus qualified for the [[1972 Winter Olympics]], but were not permitted to participate by the Soviet authorities.<ref name=\"Yelchinarticle1\" /><ref name=\"Yelchinarticle2\" /> Yelchin said the reason was unclear: \"I don't exactly know what that was \u2013 because they were Jewish or because the [[KGB]] didn't want them to travel.\"<ref name=\"itgeek\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/08/19/anton-yelchin-is-new-hollywood-it-geek.html|title=Hollywood's New 'It' Geek|last=Stern|first=Marlow|date=August 19, 2011|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nYelchin's family left for the United States in September 1989, when Anton was six months old, and were thereafter granted refugee status from the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]].<ref name=\"Yelchinarticle1\" /><ref name=\"Yelchinarticle2\" /> His mother worked as a [[figure skating]] choreographer and his father as a figure skating coach, having been [[Sasha Cohen]]'s first trainer.<ref name=\"Yelchin3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/entertainment/ci_4963201 |title=''Dog'' star a veteran at 17 |date=January 6, 2007 |publisher=Pasadena Star News |accessdate=January 7, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928093738/http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/entertainment/ci_4963201 |archivedate=September 28, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"buzzine\">{{cite news|url=http://www.buzzinefilm.com/interviews/film-interview-anton-yelchin-charlie-bartlett-star-trek-01302008|title=On Top of the Teenage World as 'Charlie Bartlett' & as Pavel Chekov in 'Star Trek' Reboot|last=Itier|first=Emmanuel|date=January 30, 2008|work=Buzzine|accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref> Yelchin's uncle is the children's author and painter [[Eugene Yelchin]].<ref name=\"Yelchinarticle1\" /> In an article published in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' in December 1989, Yelchin's mother stated, \"A woman came up, saw Anton, and said, 'He's beautiful. He will be actor.'\"<ref name=\"Yelchinarticle1\" /> Yelchin stated that he \"wasn't very good\" at figure skating, his parents' profession.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2011/10/26/trek_co_star_yelchin_finds_love_in_like_crazy/?page=full|title=Trek' co-star Yelchin finds love in 'Like Crazy'|last=Germain|first=David|date=October 26, 2011|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> \n\nYelchin was born with [[cystic fibrosis]]. However, details of his medical condition were only revealed in 2017 after his death by a foundation established in his name, the Anton Yelchin Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Anton Yelchin|url=http://www.antonyelchinfoundation.org/about|website=Anton Yelchin Foundation|accessdate=March 29, 2018|quote=Anton did not share details about his medical challenges with the public, but he suffered from Cystic Fibrosis from an early age.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/anton-yelchin-apos-parents-just-181743478.html|title=Anton Yelchin's parents just settled a major lawsuit over his death, and we hope this helps bring them closure|work=Yahoo.com|last=Levy|first=Genelle|date=March 23, 2018|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref> \n\nYelchin attended the [[Sherman Oaks Center for Enriched Studies]] in [[Tarzana, Los Angeles|Tarzana, California]],<ref name=\"Yelchin3\" /> and enrolled at the [[University of Southern California]] in the fall of 2007 to study film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/people/archive/peoplearchive.php/Anton_Yelchin/biography|title=Anton Yelchin Biography|publisher=M&C|accessdate=May 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Anton Yelchin 2011.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Yelchin in September 2011]]\nAfter his film debut in ''[[A Man Is Mostly Water]]'', Yelchin's early roles in both film and television included ''A Time for Dancing'',<ref name=\"Ask\">{{cite web|title=Anton Yelchin|url=http://www.askmen.com/celebs/men/entertainment/anton-yelchin/|work=AskMen - Become A Better Man|publisher=IGN Entertainment, Inc|accessdate=June 19, 2012|author=Staff|year=1996\u20132012}}</ref> ''[[Delivering Milo]]'', ''[[House of D]]'' and ''Taken''. He guest-starred in the Season Four episode of ''[[Curb Your Enthusiasm]]'' as Stewart, Cheryl David's cousin and a self-described magician who knows a card trick. Yelchin played Bobby Garfield in ''[[Hearts in Atlantis (film)|Hearts in Atlantis]]'' (2001), which is based on [[Stephen King]]'s novel. He won a 2002 [[Young Artist Award]] (Best Performance in a Feature Film \u2013 Leading Young Actor) for this performance.\n\nIn [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s television series ''[[Huff (TV series)|Huff]]'', Yelchin played Byrd Huffstodt, the 14-year-old son of the eponymous character ([[Hank Azaria]]). In 2006, he guest-starred in the ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'' episode \"Tru Love\", as a boy who falls in love with his teacher. He also appeared in the ''[[Criminal Minds]]'' episode \"[[Sex, Birth, Death|Sex, Birth & Death]]\" as Nathan Harris, a boy who has murderous urges towards prostitutes and approaches Dr. [[Spencer Reid]] to help him before he actually does kill.\n\nIn ''[[Alpha Dog]]'', Yelchin played Zack Mazursky, a character based on real-life murder victim [[Murder of Nicholas Markowitz|Nicholas Markowitz]].<ref name=\"Yelchin3\" /> ''[[USA Today]]''{{'}}s review described Yelchin's performance as \"heartbreakingly endearing\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Puig |first=Claudia |title=''Alpha Dog'': Razor-sharp reality |work=USA Today |date=January 11, 2007 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2007-01-11-alpha-dog_x.htm |accessdate=January 26, 2007}}</ref> After the film's premiere, Markowitz's mother praised his portrayal of her son.<ref>{{cite news|title=Teenage Actor Uncomfortable With Pool Sex Scene |website=Contact Music |date=December 18, 2006 |url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/article/teenage%20actor%20uncomfortable%20with%20pool%20sex%20scene_1016857 |accessdate=December 18, 2006}}</ref> Yelchin subsequently headlined ''[[Fierce People (film)|Fierce People]]'', which received a limited release on September 7, 2007. In 2008, he played the title role in ''[[Charlie Bartlett]]'', a film about a wealthy teenager in a public high school.<ref>{{cite web|work=MovieWeb |title=Anton Yelchin, Robert Downey Jr., Hope Davis, Kat Dennings, And Tyler Hilton Go Dark For Charlie Bartlett |url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/13/13013.php |accessdate=June 12, 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060619070143/http://www.movieweb.com/news/13/13013.php| archivedate=June 19, 2006 | url-status=live}}</ref> He also appeared alongside the Russian duo [[t.A.T.u.]] in the film ''[[You and I (2008 film)|You and I]]'' (which was filmed in Moscow during the summer of 2007),<ref>{{cite news|last=Dawtrey |first=Adam |title=Mischa Barton to star in Joffe's ''t.A.T.u.'' |work=Variety |date=June 6, 2007 |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117966342.html?categoryId=19&cs=1 |accessdate=August 27, 2007}}</ref> and co-starred in ''[[Middle of Nowhere (2008 film)|Middle of Nowhere]]''.\n\nYelchin played supporting roles in two blockbuster films released in May 2009: [[Star Trek (film)|''Star Trek'']], in which he played teenage navigator [[Pavel Chekov]], and ''[[Terminator Salvation]]'', in which he played a young [[Kyle Reese]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Gregg |last=Goldstein |title=Yelchin finds ''Salvation'' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=March 19, 2008 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3ifff588c2bae9eaff4982de057e9344ff |accessdate=March 19, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419002212/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3ifff588c2bae9eaff4982de057e9344ff |archivedate=April 19, 2008 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Siegel |first=Tatiana |title=Yelchin sets course for ''Trek'' |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=August 8, 2007 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i4d705b8469ab9fb8943c401da6415f43 |accessdate=August 27, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070831160534/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i4d705b8469ab9fb8943c401da6415f43 |archivedate=August 31, 2007 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Yelchin played Charley Brewster in [[Craig Gillespie]]'s remake film ''[[Fright Night (2011 film)|Fright Night]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19720 |title=''Fright Night'' Redo Finds Its Paranoid Neighbor |date=April 6, 2010 |work=Bloody Disgusting |accessdate=July 13, 2010}}</ref> starred in the romantic drama ''[[Like Crazy]]'', and voiced Clumsy Smurf in the film adaptation of ''[[The Smurfs (film)|The Smurfs]]'' and [[The Smurfs 2|its sequel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/2010/04/05/anton-yelchin-and-fred-armisen-join-the-smurfs/ |title=Anton Yelchin and Fred Armisen Join The Smurfs |first=Peter |last=Sciretta |date=April 5, 2010 |accessdate=July 13, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100714001014/http://www.slashfilm.com/2010/04/05/anton-yelchin-and-fred-armisen-join-the-smurfs/| archivedate= July 14, 2010 | url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite interview|title=Crazy In Love \u2014 Anton Yelchin Interview| url= http://www.stevecummins.com/interviews/crazy-in-love-%E2%80%94-anton-yelchin-interview| work= SteveCummins.com| accessdate= June 19, 2012|first= Anton| last= Yelchin| interviewer= Steve Cummins | date= January 30, 2012}}</ref> He replaced [[Russell Tovey]] for the voice role of Albino Pirate in the American version of the animated film ''[[The Pirates! In an Adventure with Scientists!]]'' (also known as ''The Pirates! Band of Misfits'') (2012).<ref>{{cite web|title=The Pirates! In an Adventure with Scientists (Review)| url= http://vulturehound.co.uk/2012/03/the-pirates-in-an-adventure-with-scientists-film-review/|work=[[Vulture Hound]] Magazine|publisher=Vulture Hound Magazine|accessdate=June 19, 2012| first=Rob |last= Simpson| year= 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Pirates! Band of Misfits: Cast & Crew| url=http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-pirates-band-of-misfits/cast-crew| work= MovieWeb.com| accessdate=June 19, 2012| year=1995\u20132012}}</ref> Yelchin voiced Shun in [[Studio Ghibli]]'s  ''[[From Up on Poppy Hill]]''.\n\nYelchin again played the role of Chekov in the 2013 film ''[[Star Trek Into Darkness]]''. He also played the lead in the thriller ''[[Odd Thomas (film)|Odd Thomas]]'' (2013)<ref>{{cite web|last=Hill |first=Logan |url=https://nymag.com/movies/features/anton-yelchin-2011-10/ |title=Anton Yelchin on His Role in 'Like Crazy' |work=[[New York Magazine]] |date=October 23, 2011 |accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref> and the horror comedy ''[[Burying the Ex]]'' (2014). In 2015, Yelchin starred in the independent horror film ''[[Green Room (film)|Green Room]]'', which premiered at the Cannes film festival that year and received limited theatrical release in May 2016.\n\nShortly before his death, Yelchin reprised his role as Chekov in ''[[Star Trek Beyond]]'', which was released on July 22, 2016. He completed filming several independent films which were released posthumously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/anton-yelchin-unreleased-movies.html|title=Anton Yelchin: 4 Unreleased Movies Featuring the Late Actor|date=July 25, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Yelchin also recorded the voice role of Jim in [[Guillermo del Toro]]'s ''[[Trollhunters]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/trollhunters-anton-yelchin-kelsey-grammer-ron-perlman-cast-guillermo-del-toro-netflix-animated-series-1201773063/|title='Trollhunters': Anton Yelchin, Kelsey Grammer & Ron Perlman To Lead Cast Of Guillermo del Toro Netflix Animated Series|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=June 15, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=June 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.cartoonbrew.com/internet-television/trollhunter-trailer-first-look-guillermo-del-toros-new-series-143746.html | title= \u2018Trollhunter\u2019 Trailer: First Look at Guillermo del Toro\u2019s New Series | work= Cartoon Brew | accessdate= October 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYelchin enjoyed playing the guitar, which he said gave him a lot of fulfillment, and was a fan of acoustic [[blues music|blues]] music. He once played for a [[punk rock|punk]] band called the Hammerheads.<ref name=\"wanderl\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2011/sxsw-video-interview-anton-yelchin-from-mel-gibsons-the-beaver|title=SXSW Video Interview: Anton Yelchin for Mel Gibson's 'The Beaver'|last=Kirk|first=Jeremy|date=March 21, 2011|accessdate=March 25, 2011}}</ref> He was also interested in photography. In January 2018, an exhibit of Yelchin's photography entitled ''Anton Yelchin: Provocative Beauty'' was displayed at New York City's De Buck Gallery.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/news/2018/01/06/anton-yelchin-photography-exhibit/|title=Anton Yelchin's secret photography passion now on display|work=EW.com|last=Romano|first=Nick|date=January 6, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAnton's photography has since been critically acclaimed by various magazines around the world as exhibits continue. <ref name=\"Artribune 2019\">{{cite web | last=Kwestorowska | first=Anita | title=La fotografia di Anton Yelchin a Roma | website=Artribune | date=2019-11-17 | url=https://www.artribune.com/arti-visive/fotografia/2019/11/mostra-anton-yelchin-spazio-field-palazzo-brancaccio-roma/ | language=it | access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn June 18, 2016, when he failed to arrive at a rehearsal, Yelchin was found by friends just before midnight pinned between his [[Jeep Grand Cherokee]] and a brick pillar mailbox outside his house in [[Studio City, Los Angeles|Studio City, California]], the victim of what was described as a \"freak accident\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-anton-yelchin-jeep-rollaway-20160620-snap-story.html|title='Star Trek' actor Anton Yelchin's SUV was recalled in April over rollaway risk|last=Times|first=Los Angeles|website=latimes.com|access-date=June 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Star Trek actor Anton Yelchin dies in fatal accident |url=https://filmindustry.network/star-trek-actor-anton-yelchin-dies-fatal-accident/31377 |publisher=Film Industry Network |date=June 19, 2016}}</ref> As Yelchin got out of his car and went to check his locked gate, the vehicle apparently rolled back down his driveway, which was on a steep incline, and trapped him against the pillar and a security fence. Yelchin was pronounced dead on June 19, 2016, at the scene at the [[27 club|age of 27]],<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/19/entertainment/actor-anton-yelchin-killed/index.html|title='Star Trek' actor Anton Yelchin dies in freak car accident|publisher=CNN|accessdate=June 19, 2016}}</ref> the [[Los Angeles County Department of Medical Examiner-Coroner|Los Angeles County Coroner]]'s office identified the cause of death as \"blunt [[traumatic asphyxia]]\" and stated that there were \"no obvious suspicious circumstances involved\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/anton-yelchin-dead-accident-1.3642660|title=Actor who played Chekov in Star Trek reboot dead after being pinned by own car|website=CBC News|access-date=June 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-me-anton-yelchin-20160619-snap-story.html|title=Anton Yelchin, actor in 'Star Trek' films, dies in freak car accident at age 27|last=Mather|first=Kate|date=June 19, 2016|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 19, 2016}}</ref> \n\n===Tributes===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Anton Yelchin Grave Bronze Statue.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Yelchin's grave at Hollywood Forever Cemetery as of October, 2017]] -->\nFollowing Yelchin's death, the producers of ''Star Trek'' stated that the role of Chekov would not be recast and that the character would be written out of any subsequent ''Star Trek'' films. ''Star Trek Beyond'' was dedicated to Yelchin and [[Leonard Nimoy]], who had also died between the release of ''Star Trek Into Darkness'' and ''Star Trek Beyond''. ''[[Smurfs: The Lost Village]]'' was dedicated to Yelchin, as he had provided the voice of [[Clumsy Smurf]] in the live-action ''Smurfs'' films. Additionally, ''[[We Don't Belong Here (film)|We Don't Belong Here]]'', ''[[Rememory]]'', ''[[Porto (film)|Porto]]'', ''[[Newness (film)|Newness]]'', ''[[Thoroughbreds (2017 film)|Thoroughbreds]]'', and the first two episodes of ''[[Trollhunters]]'' are dedicated to him, with the entirety of ''Trollhunters'' being dedicated to him upon its conclusion in May 2018. Yelchin was also featured in the \"In Memoriam\" section during the [[89th Academy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oscar.go.com/news/oscar-news/oscars-in-memoriam-2017|title = Sarah Bareilles Performs \"In Memoriam\" Tribute at 2017 Oscars|last = Dove|first = Steve|website = [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]|date = February 26, 2017|accessdate = July 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, a bronze statue of Yelchin was erected at his grave in the [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]]. Celebrities present at the unveiling ceremony included [[Jennifer Lawrence]], [[Zoe Saldana]], [[Simon Pegg]], [[J. J. Abrams]], [[Emile Hirsch]], [[Demi Moore]], [[Jon Voight]], [[Drake Doremus]], and [[Jeremy Saulnier]]. Saldana spoke at the ceremony, paying tribute to Yelchin: \"It is a bittersweet moment, because we're here for Anton, and he's not here with us. But, it alleviates my heart knowing that we'll keep him alive. We're going to keep remembering him in the hopes that by practicing all the things he believed in and remembering all the love that he gave us, and all the joy he gave us, we're able to just keep him here with us.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2017/10/anton-yelchin-statue-jennifer-lawrence-jj-abrams-hollywood-forever | work = Vanity Fair | title = Jennifer Lawrence, J.J. Abrams, and More Stars Gather to Pay Respects to Anton Yelchin | accessdate = October 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/anton-yelchin-hollywood-forever-cemtery-statue-unveiling-1046959 | work = Hollywood Reporter | title = Anton Yelchin Honored By Family, 'Star Trek' Co-Stars at Statue Unveiling | accessdate = October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nYelchin was memorialised in the online video game, [[Star Trek Online]]. He received a memorial plaque alongside several other late [[Star Trek]] actors; such as [[Leonard Nimoy|Leonard Nimoy]], [[James Doohan]], and Star Trek creator [[Gene Roddenberry]].\n\nOn January 28, 2019, Viktor and Irina Yelchin premiered a documentary about their son, ''[[Love, Antosha]]'', at the [[2019 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-sundance-anton-yelchin-documentary-parents-20190124-story.html|title=Still grieving, Anton Yelchin\u2019s parents try to move forward with new documentary|first=Amy|last=Kaufman|website=latimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Lawsuit===\n[[Fiat Chrysler Automobiles]] (FCA), the manufacturer of the [[Grand Cherokee]], was aware of 2014 and 2015 models having a high rate of rollaway incidents due to a [[gearshift]] design that could make it difficult for the driver to determine whether the vehicle was in park or still in gear. FCA had already [[product recall|recalled]] all 2014\u201315 Grand Cherokees for this concern in April 2016, but the software patch to repair the vehicles did not reach dealers until the week of Yelchin's death. Following his death, FCA accelerated the recall campaign and took steps to get the affected Jeeps repaired more quickly than originally planned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/6/22/12007862/fca-jeep-grand-cherokee-gear-lever-recall-anton-yelchin|title=FCA accelerates recall of confusing gear lever that may have contributed to Anton Yelchin's death|first=Chris|last=Ziegler|date=June 22, 2016|website=The Verge}}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2016, the attorney for Yelchin's parents announced that they were planning to file a [[wrongful death]] lawsuit against Fiat Chrysler.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2016/08/01/anton-yelchin-parents-plan-sue-car-company/87938786/ |title=Anton Yelchin's parents will sue car company |publisher=USA Today |date=August 1, 2016 }}</ref> The dealership that Yelchin purchased the vehicle from stated that he was responsible for his own death, because he had allegedly \"misused\" and \"modified\" the vehicle. The dealer also asked to be removed from the lawsuit.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/chrysler-dealership-claims-anton-yelchin-deserves-blame-death-article-1.2819807| work= New York Daily News | accessdate= September 13, 2017 | title= Chrysler dealership claims Anton Yelchin's death resulted from his own 'misuse, misapplication, or damage' of Jeep}}</ref> On March 22, 2018, it was announced that Yelchin's family and Fiat Chrysler had confidentially [[settled out of court]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2018/03/22/anton-yelchin-settlement-jeep-death-court/451290002/ |title= Actor Anton Yelchin's parents reach settlement over his death caused by SUV |publisher= USA Today |date= March 22, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[A Man Is Mostly Water]]''\n| Augie\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2001\n| ''[[Delivering Milo]]''\n| Milo\n|\n|-\n| ''[[15 Minutes]]''\n| Boy in Burning Building\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Along Came a Spider (film)|Along Came a Spider]]''\n| Dimitri Starodubov\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Hearts in Atlantis (film)|Hearts in Atlantis]]''\n| Bobby Garfield\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2002\n| ''A Time for Dancing''\n| Jackson\n|\n|-\n| ''Rooftop Kisses''\n| Charlie\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[House of D]]''\n| Tommy Warshaw\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Fierce People (film)|Fierce People]]''\n| Finn Earl\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Alpha Dog]]''\n| Zack Mazursky\n| \n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Charlie Bartlett]]''\n| Charlie Bartlett\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2008\n| ''[[New York, I Love You]]''\n| Boy in the Park\n| Segment: \"Brett Ratner\"\