bruary 1997\n{{WDL|60|29|15|16}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Attilio Lombardo]]<ref group=upper-alpha>Player-Manager</ref>\n|align=left| 13 March 1998\n|align=left| 29 April 1998\n{{WDL|7|2|0|5}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Steve Bruce]]\n|align=left| 30 May 2001\n|align=left| 31 October 2001\n{{WDL|18|11|2|5}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Trevor Francis]]\n|align=left| 30 November 2001\n|align=left| 18 April 2003\n{{WDL|78|28|22|28}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Iain Dowie]]\n|align=left| 22 December 2003\n|align=left| 22 May 2006\n{{WDL|123|50|29|44}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Peter Taylor (footballer born 1953)|Peter Taylor]]\n|align=left|13 June 2006\n|align=left|8 October 2007\n{{WDL|60|21|16|23}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Neil Warnock]]\n|align=left|11 October 2007<br />27 August 2014\n|align=left|2 March 2010<br />27 December 2014\n{{WDL|146|50|45|51}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Paul Hart]]\n|align=left|2 March 2010\n|align=left|3 May 2010\n{{WDL|14|3|6|5}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[George Burley]]\n|align=left|17 June 2010\n|align=left|1 January 2011\n{{WDL|25|7|5|13}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Dougie Freedman]]\n|align=left|11 January 2011\n|align=left|23 October 2012\n{{WDL|90|32|27|31}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Ian Holloway]]\n|align=left|3 November 2012\n|align=left|23 October 2013\n{{WDL|46|14|14|18}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Tony Pulis]]\n|align=left|23 November 2013\n|align=left|14 August 2014\n{{WDL|28|12|5|11}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Alan Pardew]]\n|align=left|2 January 2015\n|align=left|22 December 2016\n{{WDL|87|35|13|39}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Sam Allardyce]]\n|align=left|23 December 2016\n|align=left|23 May 2017\n{{WDL|24|9|3|12}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Frank de Boer]]\n|align=left|26 June 2017\n|align=left|11 September 2017\n{{WDL|5|1|0|4}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[Roy Hodgson]]\n|align=left|12 September 2017\n|align=left|''Incumbent''\n{{WDL|113|41|28|44}}\n|}\n\n==Honours and achievements==\n===League===\n* '''[[List of English football champions|English top tier (currently the Premier League)]]'''\n** Highest finish 3rd place: [[1990\u201391 Football League|1990\u201391]]\n* '''[[List of winners of English Football League Championship and predecessors|English second tier (currently the EFL Championship)]]''' \n** '''Champions (2):''' [[1978\u201379 Football League|1978\u201379]], [[1993\u201394 Football League|1993\u201394]]\n** Runners-up (1): [[1968\u201369 Football League|1968\u201369]]\n** '''Play-off winners (4)''': [[1989 Football League play-offs|1988\u201389]], [[1997 Football League play-offs|1996\u201397]], [[2004 Football League play-offs|2003\u201304]], [[2013 Football League play-offs|2012\u201313]]\n** Play-off runners-up (1): [[1996 Football League play-offs|1995\u201396]]\n* '''[[List of winners of English Football League One and predecessors|English third tier (currently EFL League One)]]''' \n** '''Champions (1):''' [[1920\u201321 Football League|1920\u201321]] \n** Runners-up (4): [[1928\u201329 Football League|1928\u201329]] (South), [[1930\u201331 Football League|1930\u201331]] (South), [[1938\u201339 Football League|1938\u201339]] (South), [[1963\u201364 Football League|1963\u201364]] \n* '''[[List of winners of English Football League Two and predecessors|English fourth tier (currently EFL League Two)]]''' \n** Runners-up (1): [[1960\u201361 Football League|1960\u201361]]\n\n===Cup===\n* '''[[FA Cup]]'''\n** Runners-up (2): [[1990 FA Cup Final|1989\u201390]], [[2016 FA Cup Final|2015\u201316]]\n* '''[[Full Members Cup]]'''<ref group=upper-alpha>This was an [[association football]] cup competition held from 1985 to 1992. It was also known under its sponsored names of the '''[[Simod]] Cup''' from 1987 to 1989 and the '''[[Zenith Data Systems]] Cup''' from 1989 to 1992. The competition was created after the [[Heysel Stadium disaster]], when English clubs were banned from [[UEFA#Competitions|European competition]], as an additional competition for clubs in the top two divisions</ref>\n** '''Winners (1):''' [[1991 Full Members Cup Final|1990\u201391]]\n* '''[[FA Youth Cup]]'''\n** '''Winners (2):''' 1976\u201377, 1977\u201378\n** Runners-up (2): 1991\u201392, 1996\u201397\n\n===Wartime===\n* '''[[Football League North and South|South Regional League]]'''\n**'''Champions (1):''' [[1940\u201341 in English football|1940\u201341]]\n*'''[[Wartime League|South League 'D']]'''\n**'''Champions (1):''' [[1939-40 in English football|1939\u201340]]\n\n===Regional===\n* '''[[Southern Football League|Southern Football League Division One]]'''\n**Runners-up (1): [[1913\u201314 Southern Football League|1913\u201314]]\n* '''[[Southern Football League|Southern Football League Division Two]]'''\n**'''Champions (1):''' [[1905\u201306 Southern Football League|1905\u201306]]\n* '''United League'''<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Royals Record|title=United League|url=http://www.royalsrecord.co.uk/cups/united.html|accessdate=31 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412045405/http://www.royalsrecord.co.uk/cups/united.html|archive-date=12 April 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n**'''Champions (1):''' 1906\u201307\n** Runners-up (1): 1905\u201306\n* '''[[Southern Professional Floodlit Cup]]'''\n** Runners-up (1): 1958\u201359\n* '''[[London Challenge Cup]]'''<ref group=upper-alpha>This was a [[association football|football]] tournament organised by the [[London Football Association|London FA]]. The London Challenge Cup was first contested in 1908, and other than during the World Wars, was contested every season until 1974, when the tournament was disbanded.</ref>\n**'''Winners (3):''' 1912\u201313, 1913\u201314, 1920\u201321\n** Runners-up (6): 1919\u201320, 1921\u201322, 1922\u201323, 1931\u201332, 1937\u201338, 1946\u201347\n* '''[[Surrey Senior Cup]]'''<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Surrey FA |title=Saturday Senior Cup Previous Winners |url=http://www.surreyfa.com/previous-winners-and-officials/saturday-senior-cup-previous-winners |accessdate=31 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502232940/http://www.surreyfa.com/previous-winners-and-officials/saturday-senior-cup-previous-winners |archivedate= 2 May 2014 }}</ref>\n**'''Winners (3):''' 1996\u201397, 2000\u201301, 2001\u201302\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn the 1999 [[Michael Winterbottom]] film ''[[Wonderland (1999 film)|Wonderland]]'', the scenes of the character Dan and his son at a football match were filmed at [[Selhurst Park]] during Palace's 1\u20131 draw against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on 6 February 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1999-02-06|publisher=Statto.com|title=Results saturday 6th February 1999|date=17 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526020629/http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1999-02-06|archivedate=26 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the [[Mike Leigh]] play ''[[Abigail's Party]]'', the character Tony mentions that he used to play professionally for Crystal Palace but it \"didn't work out\", something actor [[John Salthouse]] brought to the character in rehearsals based on his own life.<ref name=\"Duvitski 6\"/> Salthouse also incorporated the club into the children's television series he wrote, ''[[Hero to Zero]]'', in which the father of the main character once played for Palace reserves.<ref>{{cite news|last=Maume|first=Chris|title=Owen's method is latest pitch at football's screen test|newspaper=The Independent|page=28|date=26 February 2000}}</ref> In the first series of ''[[Only Fools and Horses]]'' a Crystal Palace scarf could be seen on the coat rack, placed there by producer [[Ray Butt]], even though Rodney's middle name was Charlton, as Del revealed on Rodney's wedding day: their mother was a fan of \"Athletic\" not \"Heston\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Simons|first=Raoul|title=Football Talk|newspaper=The Evening Standard|date=25 May 2006|page=59}}</ref> Headmaster Keith Blackwell, who played Crystal Palace mascot \"Pete the Eagle\" in the late nineties, fronted a series of Coca-Cola advertisements in 1996. Blackwell spoke about his role and the embarrassment it brought to his family, and clips of him in costume were used in the campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last=Earls|first=John|title=Game for a laugh; Soccer club mascots keep thousands of fans entertained at every game by dressing up as lions, dinosaurs \u2013 and even a giant hammer! But what makes them want to face the taunts of cheeky away fans?|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Game+for+a+laugh%3B+Soccer+club+mascots+keep+thousands+of+fans...-a061132570|accessdate=28 June 2013|newspaper=The People|date=19 October 1997|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223317/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Game+for+a+laugh%3B+Soccer+club+mascots+keep+thousands+of+fans...-a061132570|archive-date=2 December 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Leach |first=Conrad |title=Mascot men, mascot cats and dogs |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/mascot-men-mascot-cats-and-dogs-1185112.html |accessdate=28 June 2013 |newspaper=The Independent |date=15 November 1998 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218170439/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/mascot-men-mascot-cats-and-dogs-1185112.html |archivedate=18 December 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe 2008 episode of ''[[The IT Crowd]]'', \"[[List of The IT Crowd episodes|Are We Not Men?]]\", used Selhurst Park to film the crowd scenes.\n\nAfter the band [[The Dave Clark Five]] performed \"[[Glad All Over]]\" at Selhurst Park in 1968, the song became synonymous with the team, and the Palace fans sing it at every match.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.croydonadvertiser.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/crystal-palace-fans-sing-glad-433141|title=Why do Crystal Palace fans sing Glad All Over and what are its lyrics?|last=Booker|first=James|date=19 May 2016|work=croydonadvertiser|access-date=20 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115075645/http://www.croydonadvertiser.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/crystal-palace-fans-sing-glad-433141|archive-date=15 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Crystal Palace Women==\n{{details|Crystal Palace F.C. (Women)}} <!-- NOTE: Please make detailed additions to the [[Crystal Palace L.F.C.]] article -->\n[[Crystal Palace F.C. (Women)]] is the women's football club affiliated to Crystal Palace, founded in 1992. They are managed by Dean Davenport. The team play in the FA Women's Premier League South, the third tier of English women's football.<ref name=\"ladies\">{{cite web|title=Crystal Palace Ladies FC|url=http://www.crystalpalaceladiesfc.co.uk/|accessdate=27 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701042343/http://www.crystalpalaceladiesfc.co.uk/|archive-date=1 July 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> They play their home games at the [[Hayes Lane]], Bromley, London.<ref name=\"ladies\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n;Bibliography\n*{{cite book|last=King|first=Ian|title=Crystal Palace: The Complete Record 1905\u20132011|publisher=Derby Books Publishing Company Limited|year=2012|isbn=978-1-78091-221-9}}\n* Matthews, Tony (editor). ''We All Follow The Palace''. Juma, 1998. {{ISBN|1-872204-55-4}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''The Crystal Palace Story'' by Roy Peskett, published by Roy Peskett Publishing Ltd (1969).\n* ''100 Years of Crystal Palace Football Club'' by Rev. Nigel Sands, published by The History Press Ltd, (2005), {{ISBN|978-0-7524-3608-1}}.\n* ''Crystal Palace Football Club'' by Rev. Nigel Sands, published by NPI Media Group, (1999), {{ISBN|978-0-7524-1544-4}}.\n* ''Classic Matches: Crystal Palace FC'' by Rev. Nigel Sands, published by The History Press Ltd, (2002), {{ISBN|978-0-7524-2733-1}}.\n* ''Crystal Palace Miscellany'' by Neil McSteen, published by Legends Publishing, (2009), {{ISBN|978-1-905411-55-9}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Association football|English football|London}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{BBC Football Info|BBClinkname=crystal-palace}}\n* {{official website|http://www.cpfc.co.uk/}}\n* [http://www.cpfc.org/ CPFC BBS online fans forum]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060206043559/http://www.palaceradio.net/ Palace Radio 1278am]\n* [http://www.cpfc86.co.uk/ Unofficial Records Site]\n\n{{Crystal Palace F.C.}}\n{{Crystal Palace F.C. seasons}}\n{{Crystal Palace F.C. matches}}\n{{Premier League}}\n{{Football in London}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crystal Palace F.C. 1905}}\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1905]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Premier League clubs]]\n[[Category:Former English Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in London]]\n[[Category:Southern Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:1905 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace, London]]\n[[Category:Companies that have entered administration in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c4:3394:7700:a0c1:b3ff:84ce:af76", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_Palace_F.C."}
{"title_page": "\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish idiom meaning \"soldiers of Ireland\" or \"volunteers of Ireland\"}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n\n'''\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann''' ({{IPA-ga|\u02c8o\u02d0\u0261\u026b\u032ai\u02d0 n\u032a\u02e0\u0259 \u02c8he\u02d0\u027e\u02b2\u0259n\u032a\u02e0|-|\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann.ogg}}), abbreviated '''\u00d3\u00c9''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.military.ie/en/info-centre/defence-forces-2016/easter-parade-2016/|title=Easter Parade 2016 - Defence Forces 2016 - Info Centre - Defence Forces|publisher=}}</ref> is an [[Irish language|Irish-language]] [[idiom]] that can be translated variously as ''soldiers of Ireland'',<ref>[http://www.military.ie/dfhq/pubrel/publications/DFHistory.pdf A Pictorial History of \u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann, the Defence Forces of Ireland] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118204316/http://www.military.ie/dfhq/pubrel/publications/DFHistory.pdf |date=18 November 2007 }}, Irish Defence Forces</ref> ''warriors of Ireland'',<ref>White, Robert William. ''Provisional Irish republicans: an oral and interpretive history''. Greenwood Publishing Group, 1993. p 33.</ref><ref>Pollard, Tony. ''Scorched Earth: Studies in the Archaeology of Conflict''. BRILL, 2007. p 84.</ref> ''[[Volunteer (Irish republican)|volunteers]] of Ireland''<ref name=\"O'Leary\">O'Leary, Brendan. ''Terror, insurgency, and the state: ending protracted conflicts''. University of Pennsylvania Press, 2007. p 190.</ref><ref>English, Richard. ''Armed struggle: the history of the IRA''. Pan Macmillan, 2004. p 10.</ref> or ''Irish volunteers''.<ref name=\"O'Leary\"/><ref>Gerry White, Brendan O'Shea, Bill Younghusband. ''Irish Volunteer soldier 1913\u201323''. Osprey Publishing, 2003. p 8.</ref><ref>Coogan, Tim Pat. ''The IRA''. Palgrave Macmillan, 2002. p 45.</ref> In traditional [[Gaelic type|Gaelic script]], it is written '''\u00d3gla\u0131\u0121 na h\u00c9\u0131reann'''.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann.jpg|thumb|[[Irish Defence Forces cap badge|Cap badge]] of the [[Irish Defence Forces]]. ''\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann'' and ''Fianna F\u00e1il'' (FF) are both idioms that can be translated as ''warriors of Ireland''.]] -->\n\n== Origins, Irish Volunteers ==\n''\u00d3glach'', the singular of \u00f3glaigh, comes from the [[Old Irish language|Old Irish]] word ''\u00f3clach'', meaning a young man or (by analogy) a young warrior.<ref>C. Marstrander, E. G. Quin et al., editors (1913\u201376), \u201c[http://edil.qub.ac.uk/33460 \u00f3clach]\u201d, in Dictionary of the Irish Language: Based Mainly on Old and Middle Irish Materials, Dublin: Royal Irish Academy, </ref>The phrase ''\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann'' was coined as an Irish-language title for the [[Irish Volunteers]] of 1913,<ref>Richard English, 2003, Armed struggle: the history of the IRA, Oxford University Press: Oxford</ref> and it was retained despite the Volunteers becoming known in English as the [[Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) during the [[Irish War of Independence|War of Independence]] of 1919\u20131922.\n\n== Irish Republican Army ==\nThe name has also been used by [[List of organisations known as the Irish Republican Army|several other paramilitary groups calling themselves the Irish Republican Army]] since 1920. These groups each claim to be the sole [[Irish republican legitimatism|legitimist]] modern successors to the original Irish Volunteers and Irish Republican Army, and they have refused to recognise the authority of (variously) the Defence Forces, [[Northern Ireland]] and the [[Republic of Ireland]]; as such, each of these groups claims the sole right to use the name ''\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann''. Such groups have included the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|Provisional IRA]],<ref>[http://www.cfr.org/terrorist-organizations/provisional-irish-republican-army-ira-aka-pira-provos-glaigh-na-hireann-uk-separatists/p9240 Provisional Irish Republican Army (IRA) (aka, PIRA, \"the provos,\" \u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann) (UK separatists) \u2013 Council on Foreign Relations]. Cfr.org.</ref> the [[Continuity Irish Republican Army|Continuity IRA]]<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/cira.htm Continuity Irish Republican Army (CIRA)]. Globalsecurity.org.</ref> and the [[Real Irish Republican Army|Real IRA]].<ref>[http://www.tribune.ie/news/home-news/article/2009/apr/12/statement-from-the-real-ira-to-be-read-out-at-the-/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415040726/http://www.tribune.ie/news/home-news/article/2009/apr/12/statement-from-the-real-ira-to-be-read-out-at-the-/ |date=15 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\nSome IRA splinter groups have used ''Oglaigh na h\u00c9ireann'' in English-language contexts, abandoning the label ''Irish Republican Army''. An early instance was formed in 1956 by members of the Dublin Brigade who followed [[Joe Christle]] after his expulsion from the IRA; they formed an alliance with [[Saor Uladh]] shortly before [[Border Campaign (Irish Republican Army)|the IRA's Border Campaign]] eclipsed them.<ref>{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Lawrence William |title=Christle, Joseph Patrick |url=https://dib.cambridge.org/viewReadPage.do?articleId=a9266 |url-access=subscription |website=Dictionary of Irish Biography |publisher=Cambridge University Press |accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref> Two [[dissident republican]] groups formed in the 2000s were named ''Oglaigh na h\u00c9ireann'': [[\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann (CIRA splinter group)|a Continuity IRA splinter group]] first reported on by the [[Independent Monitoring Commission]] in 2006,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/special/2006/imcfeb1/index.pdf |title=Eighth Report of the Independent Monitoring Commission |accessdate=6 June 2010 |publisher=The Irish Times |date=January 2006 }}</ref> and [[\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann (Real IRA splinter group)|a Real IRA splinter group]] which began claiming responsibility for attacks in 2009.\n\nA suppression order made by the Irish state in June 1939 under the [[Offences against the State Acts 1939\u20131998|Offences Against the State Act 1939]] stated that \"the organisation styling itself the Irish Republican Army (also the I.R.A. and Oglaigh [sic] na h\u00c9ireann)\" was to be considered an unlawful organisation within the context of the Act.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1939/en/si/0162.html S.I. No. 162/1939 \u2013 Unlawful Organisation (Suppression) Order, 1939]. Irishstatutebook.ie (30 June 2007).</ref>\n\n== National Army ==\nIn 1922, the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]] created the [[Irish Free State]], and its [[Provisional Government of the Irish Free State|Provisional Government]] formed the [[National Army (Ireland)|National Army]]. To establish itself as carrying on the tradition of the pre-independence movement, the Army adopted ''\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann'' as its Irish language name,<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=9ftdDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA331&dq=irish+defence+forces+oglaigh#v=onepage&q=irish%20defence%20forces%20oglaigh&f=false | title=The Handbook of European Defence Policies and Armed Forces| isbn=9780198790501| last1=Meijer| first1=Hugo| last2=Wyss| first2=Marco| date=11 July 2018}}</ref> and also adopted the cap badge and buttons of the Irish Volunteers; the badge incorporates the title in its design.<ref>[http://www.military.ie/info-centre/defence-forces-history/defence-forces-cap-badge/ Defence Forces Headquarters \u2013 History: Defence Forces Cap Badge]. Military.ie.</ref>\n\n== Defence Forces ==\nSince 1924, ''\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann'' has remained the official Irish-language title for the [[Defence Forces (Ireland)|Defence Forces]],<ref>[http://www.military.ie/irish/index.html Arm \u2013 \u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann] \u2014 use on the official website of the Irish Defence Forces, retrieved 29 November 2006.</ref> which are recognised by the [[Irish Government]] as the only legitimate armed forces of the independent state on the island of Ireland.<ref>From 1922 to 1937, this state was the [[Irish Free State]], and since 1937 was Ireland or [[\u00c9ire]]. The Irish Government passed an act in 1948 under which the name ''[[Republic of Ireland]]'' can also be used in English-language legal documents as a description of the state.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oglaigh na hEireann}}\n[[Category:Military of the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish Republican Army]]\n[[Category:Military history of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish words and phrases]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish idiom meaning \"soldiers of Ireland\" or \"volunteers of Ireland\"}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n\n'''\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann''' ({{IPA-ga|\u02c8o\u02d0\u0261\u026b\u032ai\u02d0 n\u032a\u02e0\u0259 \u02c8he\u02d0\u027e\u02b2\u0259n\u032a\u02e0|-|\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann.ogg}}), abbreviated '''\u00d3\u00c9''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.military.ie/en/info-centre/defence-forces-2016/easter-parade-2016/|title=Easter Parade 2016 - Defence Forces 2016 - Info Centre - Defence Forces|publisher=}}</ref> is an [[Irish language|Irish-language]] [[idiom]] that can be translated variously as ''soldiers of Ireland'',<ref>[http://www.military.ie/dfhq/pubrel/publications/DFHistory.pdf A Pictorial History of \u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann, the Defence Forces of Ireland] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118204316/http://www.military.ie/dfhq/pubrel/publications/DFHistory.pdf |date=18 November 2007 }}, Irish Defence Forces</ref> ''warriors of Ireland'',<ref>White, Robert William. ''Provisional Irish republicans: an oral and interpretive history''. Greenwood Publishing Group, 1993. p 33.</ref><ref>Pollard, Tony. ''Scorched Earth: Studies in the Archaeology of Conflict''. BRILL, 2007. p 84.</ref> ''[[Volunteer (Irish republican)|volunteers]] of Ireland''<ref name=\"O'Leary\">O'Leary, Brendan. ''Terror, insurgency, and the state: ending protracted conflicts''. University of Pennsylvania Press, 2007. p 190.</ref><ref>English, Richard. ''Armed struggle: the history of the IRA''. Pan Macmillan, 2004. p 10.</ref> or ''Irish volunteers''.<ref name=\"O'Leary\"/><ref>Gerry White, Brendan O'Shea, Bill Younghusband. ''Irish Volunteer soldier 1913\u201323''. Osprey Publishing, 2003. p 8.</ref><ref>Coogan, Tim Pat. ''The IRA''. Palgrave Macmillan, 2002. p 45.</ref> In traditional [[Gaelic type|Gaelic script]], it is written ''''\u00d3gla\u0131\u0121 na h\u00c9\u0131reann'''.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann.jpg|thumb|[[Irish Defence Forces cap badge|Cap badge]] of the [[Irish Defence Forces]]. ''\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann'' and ''Fianna F\u00e1il'' (FF) are both idioms that can be translated as ''warriors of Ireland''.]] -->\n\n== Origins, Irish Volunteers ==\n''\u00d3glach'', the singular of \u00f3glaigh, comes from the [[Old Irish language|Old Irish]] word ''\u00f3clach'', meaning a young man or (by analogy) a young warrior.<ref>C. Marstrander, E. G. Quin et al., editors (1913\u201376), \u201c[http://edil.qub.ac.uk/33460 \u00f3clach]\u201d, in Dictionary of the Irish Language: Based Mainly on Old and Middle Irish Materials, Dublin: Royal Irish Academy, </ref>The phrase ''\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann'' was coined as an Irish-language title for the [[Irish Volunteers]] of 1913,<ref>Richard English, 2003, Armed struggle: the history of the IRA, Oxford University Press: Oxford</ref> and it was retained despite the Volunteers becoming known in English as the [[Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) during the [[Irish War of Independence|War of Independence]] of 1919\u20131922.\n\n== Irish Republican Army ==\nThe name has also been used by [[List of organisations known as the Irish Republican Army|several other paramilitary groups calling themselves the Irish Republican Army]] since 1920. These groups each claim to be the sole [[Irish republican legitimatism|legitimist]] modern successors to the original Irish Volunteers and Irish Republican Army, and they have refused to recognise the authority of (variously) the Defence Forces, [[Northern Ireland]] and the [[Republic of Ireland]]; as such, each of these groups claims the sole right to use the name ''\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann''. Such groups have included the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|Provisional IRA]],<ref>[http://www.cfr.org/terrorist-organizations/provisional-irish-republican-army-ira-aka-pira-provos-glaigh-na-hireann-uk-separatists/p9240 Provisional Irish Republican Army (IRA) (aka, PIRA, \"the provos,\" \u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann) (UK separatists) \u2013 Council on Foreign Relations]. Cfr.org.</ref> the [[Continuity Irish Republican Army|Continuity IRA]]<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/cira.htm Continuity Irish Republican Army (CIRA)]. Globalsecurity.org.</ref> and the [[Real Irish Republican Army|Real IRA]].<ref>[http://www.tribune.ie/news/home-news/article/2009/apr/12/statement-from-the-real-ira-to-be-read-out-at-the-/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415040726/http://www.tribune.ie/news/home-news/article/2009/apr/12/statement-from-the-real-ira-to-be-read-out-at-the-/ |date=15 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\nSome IRA splinter groups have used ''Oglaigh na h\u00c9ireann'' in English-language contexts, abandoning the label ''Irish Republican Army''. An early instance was formed in 1956 by members of the Dublin Brigade who followed [[Joe Christle]] after his expulsion from the IRA; they formed an alliance with [[Saor Uladh]] shortly before [[Border Campaign (Irish Republican Army)|the IRA's Border Campaign]] eclipsed them.<ref>{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Lawrence William |title=Christle, Joseph Patrick |url=https://dib.cambridge.org/viewReadPage.do?articleId=a9266 |url-access=subscription |website=Dictionary of Irish Biography |publisher=Cambridge University Press |accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref> Two [[dissident republican]] groups formed in the 2000s were named ''Oglaigh na h\u00c9ireann'': [[\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann (CIRA splinter group)|a Continuity IRA splinter group]] first reported on by the [[Independent Monitoring Commission]] in 2006,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/special/2006/imcfeb1/index.pdf |title=Eighth Report of the Independent Monitoring Commission |accessdate=6 June 2010 |publisher=The Irish Times |date=January 2006 }}</ref> and [[\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann (Real IRA splinter group)|a Real IRA splinter group]] which began claiming responsibility for attacks in 2009.\n\nA suppression order made by the Irish state in June 1939 under the [[Offences against the State Acts 1939\u20131998|Offences Against the State Act 1939]] stated that \"the organisation styling itself the Irish Republican Army (also the I.R.A. and Oglaigh [sic] na h\u00c9ireann)\" was to be considered an unlawful organisation within the context of the Act.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1939/en/si/0162.html S.I. No. 162/1939 \u2013 Unlawful Organisation (Suppression) Order, 1939]. Irishstatutebook.ie (30 June 2007).</ref>\n\n== National Army ==\nIn 1922, the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]] created the [[Irish Free State]], and its [[Provisional Government of the Irish Free State|Provisional Government]] formed the [[National Army (Ireland)|National Army]]. To establish itself as carrying on the tradition of the pre-independence movement, the Army adopted ''\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann'' as its Irish language name,<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=9ftdDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA331&dq=irish+defence+forces+oglaigh#v=onepage&q=irish%20defence%20forces%20oglaigh&f=false | title=The Handbook of European Defence Policies and Armed Forces| isbn=9780198790501| last1=Meijer| first1=Hugo| last2=Wyss| first2=Marco| date=11 July 2018}}</ref> and also adopted the cap badge and buttons of the Irish Volunteers; the badge incorporates the title in its design.<ref>[http://www.military.ie/info-centre/defence-forces-history/defence-forces-cap-badge/ Defence Forces Headquarters \u2013 History: Defence Forces Cap Badge]. Military.ie.</ref>\n\n== Defence Forces ==\nSince 1924, ''\u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann'' has remained the official Irish-language title for the [[Defence Forces (Ireland)|Defence Forces]],<ref>[http://www.military.ie/irish/index.html Arm \u2013 \u00d3glaigh na h\u00c9ireann] \u2014 use on the official website of the Irish Defence Forces, retrieved 29 November 2006.</ref> which are recognised by the [[Irish Government]] as the only legitimate armed forces of the independent state on the island of Ireland.<ref>From 1922 to 1937, this state was the [[Irish Free State]], and since 1937 was Ireland or [[\u00c9ire]]. The Irish Government passed an act in 1948 under which the name ''[[Republic of Ireland]]'' can also be used in English-language legal documents as a description of the state.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oglaigh na hEireann}}\n[[Category:Military of the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish Republican Army]]\n[[Category:Military history of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish words and phrases]]\n", "name_user": "Kwekubo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%93glaigh_na_h%C3%89ireann"}
{"title_page": "John Bassett", "text_new": "{{distinguish|John Bassette}}\n{{Other people|John Bassett}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image       = \n|alt         = \n|caption     = \n|birth_name  = John White Hughes Bassett\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1915|8|25}}\n|birth_place = [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1998|4|27|1915|8|25}}\n|death_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n|other_names = \n|known_for   = \n|occupation  = Media proprietor, politician\n|nationality = \n|awards      = [[Order of Canada]]<br />[[Order of Ontario]]\n}}\n'''John White Hughes Bassett''',  {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|CC|OOnt}} (August 25, 1915 &ndash; April 27, 1998) was a Canadian media proprietor and politician.\n\nBorn in [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], he was the son of [[John Bassett Sr.|John Bassett]] (1886\u20131958), publisher of the ''[[Montreal Gazette]]'', and Marion Avery (n\u00e9e Wright).\n\n==Education==\nBassett attended Ashbury College and graduated from [[Bishop's University]] with a BA in 1936.\n\n==Politics==\nAfter fighting with the Army in [[World War II]], Bassett ran unsuccessfully for the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada]], in the [[1945 Canadian federal election|1945 Canadian election]] in the riding of [[Sherbrooke (electoral district)|Sherbrooke]], losing to Liberal incumbent, [[Maurice Gingues]]. He also ran in the [[1962 Canadian federal election|1962 election]] in the riding of [[Spadina (electoral district)|Spadina]] losing to Liberal candidate [[Perry Ryan (Canadian politician)|Perry Ryan]] by less than 2,000 votes.\n\n==Publishing and broadcasting==\nHe became a [[reporter]] for [[Toronto]]'s ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' newspaper after graduating from university. After World War II, he was hired by the ''[[Toronto Telegram]]'' as advertising director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalism.ryerson.ca/m3694/ |title=An Officer and a Journalist |work=Ryerson Review of Journalism |publisher=The Ryerson School of Journalism |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305001307/http://www.journalism.ryerson.ca/m3694/ |archivedate=2016-03-05 }}</ref> His first experience in newspaper ownership was with the ''[[Sherbrooke Daily Record]]'', which he bought from his father. In 1952, Bassett purchased part ownership of the ''Toronto Telegram''. In 1960, he founded [[Telegram Corporation|Baton Broadcasting]] to run [[Toronto]]'s first commercial [[television station]], [[CFTO-TV]].  A few months later, he won the television rights to the [[Canadian Football League East Division|Eastern Conference of the Canadian Football League]].  He needed a network in order to broadcast the games.  The result was the Canadian Television Network, later to become [[CTV Television Network|CTV]], with CFTO as the flagship station.  Starting in the 1980s, Bassett began a drive to take over CTV by buying as many stations as possible.  He succeeded in 1997, a year before his death.\n\n==Sports==\nFrom 1957 to 1974, Bassett was the owner of the [[Toronto Argonauts]], a team in the [[Canadian Football League]].\n\nIn 1957, he was named to the \"Silver Seven,\" a committee that oversaw hockey operations for the  [[Toronto Maple Leafs]]. In 1961, longtime Maple Leafs owner [[Conn Smythe]] sold most of his shares in Maple Leaf Gardens Ltd. (which owned the Maple Leafs and [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]) to a partnership of his son [[Stafford Smythe|Stafford]], [[Toronto Marlboros]] president [[Harold Ballard]] and Bassett for $2.3 million.  Conn later claimed that he thought he was selling only to his son, but it is very unlikely that Stafford would have been able to raise the money on his own. Bassett became chairman of the Gardens' board of directors, when Smythe resigned shortly after Toronto won the Stanley Cup in 1962. Bassett's name appears on the Stanley Cup 4 times 1962, 1963, 1964, 1967.\n\nIn 1969, Ballard and Stafford Smythe were charged with tax evasion and accused of using Maple Leaf Gardens Ltd. to pay for their personal expenses. Bassett persuaded the board to fire Smythe as president and Ballard as executive vice president. The board elected Bassett as the new president.\n\nHowever, Bassett did not force Smythe and Ballard to sell their shares, and they both remained on the board. That was a serious strategic blunder on Bassett's part; Smythe was still the largest shareholder, and he and Ballard controlled almost half the shares between them. A year later, Ballard and Smythe staged a proxy war to win back control. Faced with an untenable situation, Bassett resigned and sold his shares to Smythe and Ballard.\n\nBassett's son, [[John F. Bassett]], would follow in his father's path of becoming a professional sports owner; the younger Bassett was a part owner of the [[World Hockey Association]]'s [[Ottawa Nationals]], [[Toronto Toros]] and [[Birmingham Bulls (WHA)|Birmingham Bulls]]; the [[World Football League]]'s [[Memphis Southmen]] and the [[United States Football League]]'s [[Tampa Bay Bandits]].\n\n==Government==\nIn 1989, he was appointed for a three-year term as chairman of the [[Security Intelligence Review Committee]], an independent body that reports to the [[Parliament of Canada]] on the operations of the [[Canadian Security Intelligence Service]]. Due to the requirements under the [[Official Secrets Act]], Bassett was sworn into the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada]].\n\n==Family==\nBassett married fellow [[Bishop's University]] graduate Eleanor Moira Bradley of [[Sherbrooke]] on April 26, 1938 in the University's St. Mark's Chapel.<ref>[http://collections2.banq.qc.ca/jrn03/dn3097/src/1938/04/28/5274927_1938-04-28.txt \"BASSETT-BRADLEY\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625103609/http://collections2.banq.qc.ca/jrn03/dn3097/src/1938/04/28/5274927_1938-04-28.txt |date=2018-06-25 }} ''collections2.banq.qc.ca'' (transcript of the April 28, 1938 ''[[The Record (Sherbrooke)|The Record]]'') June 24, 2018</ref> They had three children: [[John F. Bassett|John]], [[Douglas Bassett (media executive)|Doug]], and David. After their divorce, Bassett married [[Isabel Bassett]] on July 17, 1967.<ref>[http://www.bassettbranches.org/tng/getperson.php?personID=I22&tree=42B \"Isabel Glenthorne Macdonald\"] ''bassettbranches.org'' June 24, 2018</ref> They had three children (Avery, Sarah, and Matthew) and remained together until his death.\n\nIn the 1970s, his son John was the owner of the [[Toronto Toros]], a hockey team in the [[World Hockey Association]]. Former tennis star [[Carling Bassett-Seguso]] is Bassett's granddaughter.\n\n==Honours==\n* 1985 - Made an Officer of the [[Order of Canada]].\n* 1988 - Appointed to the [[Order of Ontario]].\n* 1989 - Appointed to the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada]].\n* 1992 - Promoted to Companion of the Order of Canada.\n* 2000 - Inducted into the [[Canadian Broadcast Hall of Fame]].\n* 2003 - Inducted into the Canadian Business Hall of Fame.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Canadian honour|Type=orc|ID=719|accessdate=24 May 2010}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Conn Smythe]] | title = Principal owner, [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] | years = 1961\u20131970 (with [[Stafford Smythe]] and [[Harold Ballard]]) | after = [[Stafford Smythe]] and [[Harold Ballard]]}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[Ron Atkey]]|\n title=[[Security Intelligence Review Committee|Chair of the Security Intelligence Review Committee (Canada)]]|\n years=1989\u20131992|\n after=[[Jacques Courtois (Canadian)|Jacques Courtois]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{TorontoArgosOwner}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bassett, John}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Anglophone Quebec people]]\n[[Category:Bishop's University alumni]]\n[[Category:Burials at Grove Street Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Canadian Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Canadian mass media owners]]\n[[Category:Canadian military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1945 Canadian federal election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1962 Canadian federal election]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Members of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League executives]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League owners]]\n[[Category:Progressive Conservative Party of Canada candidates for the Canadian House of Commons]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Stanley Cup champions]]\n[[Category:Toronto Maple Leafs executives]]\n[[Category:Toronto Toros]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|John Bassette}}\n{{Other people|John Bassett}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image       = \n|alt         = \n|caption     = \n|birth_name  = John White Hughes Bassett\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1915|8|25}}\n|birth_place = [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1998|4|27|1915|8|25}}\n|death_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n|other_names = \n|known_for   = \n|occupation  = Media proprietor, politician\n|nationality = \n|awards      = [[Order of Canada]]<br />[[Order of Ontario]]\n}}\n'''John White Hughes Bassett''',  {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|CC|OOnt}} (August 25, 1915 &ndash; April 27, 1998) was a Canadian media proprietor and politician.\n\nBorn in [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], he was the son of [[John Bassett Sr.|John Bassett]] (1886\u20131958), publisher of the ''[[Montreal Gazette]]'', and Marion Avery (n\u00e9e Wright).\n\n==Education==\nBassett attended Ashbury College and graduated from [[Bishop's University]] with a BA in 1936.\n\n==Politics==\nAfter fighting with the Army in [[World War II]], Bassett ran unsuccessfully for the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada]], in the [[1945 Canadian federal election|1945 Canadian election]] in the riding of [[Sherbrooke (electoral district)|Sherbrooke]], losing to Liberal incumbent, [[Maurice Gingues]]. He also ran in the [[1962 Canadian federal election|1962 election]] in the riding of [[Spadina (electoral district)|Spadina]] losing to Liberal candidate [[Perry Ryan (Canadian politician)|Perry Ryan]] by less than 2,000 votes.\n\n==Publishing and broadcasting==\nHe became a [[reporter]] for [[Toronto]]'s ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' newspaper after graduating from university. After World War II, he was hired by the ''[[Toronto Telegram]]'' as advertising director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalism.ryerson.ca/m3694/ |title=An Officer and a Journalist |work=Ryerson Review of Journalism |publisher=The Ryerson School of Journalism |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305001307/http://www.journalism.ryerson.ca/m3694/ |archivedate=2016-03-05 }}</ref> His first experience in newspaper ownership was with the ''[[Sherbrooke Daily Record]]'', which he bought from his father. In 1952, Bassett purchased part ownership of the ''Toronto Telegram''. In 1960, he founded [[Baton Broadcasting]] to run [[Toronto]]'s first commercial [[television station]], [[CFTO-TV]].  A few months later, he won the television rights to the [[Canadian Football League East Division|Eastern Conference of the Canadian Football League]].  He needed a network in order to broadcast the games.  The result was the Canadian Television Network, later to become [[CTV Television Network|CTV]], with CFTO as the flagship station.  Starting in the 1980s, Bassett began a drive to take over CTV by buying as many stations as possible.  He succeeded in 1997, a year before his death.\n\n==Sports==\nFrom 1957 to 1974, Bassett was the owner of the [[Toronto Argonauts]], a team in the [[Canadian Football League]].\n\nIn 1957, he was named to the \"Silver Seven,\" a committee that oversaw hockey operations for the  [[Toronto Maple Leafs]]. In 1961, longtime Maple Leafs owner [[Conn Smythe]] sold most of his shares in Maple Leaf Gardens Ltd. (which owned the Maple Leafs and [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]) to a partnership of his son [[Stafford Smythe|Stafford]], [[Toronto Marlboros]] president [[Harold Ballard]] and Bassett for $2.3 million.  Conn later claimed that he thought he was selling only to his son, but it is very unlikely that Stafford would have been able to raise the money on his own. Bassett became chairman of the Gardens' board of directors, when Smythe resigned shortly after Toronto won the Stanley Cup in 1962. Bassett's name appears on the Stanley Cup 4 times 1962, 1963, 1964, 1967.\n\nIn 1969, Ballard and Stafford Smythe were charged with tax evasion and accused of using Maple Leaf Gardens Ltd. to pay for their personal expenses. Bassett persuaded the board to fire Smythe as president and Ballard as executive vice president. The board elected Bassett as the new president.\n\nHowever, Bassett did not force Smythe and Ballard to sell their shares, and they both remained on the board. That was a serious strategic blunder on Bassett's part; Smythe was still the largest shareholder, and he and Ballard controlled almost half the shares between them. A year later, Ballard and Smythe staged a proxy war to win back control. Faced with an untenable situation, Bassett resigned and sold his shares to Smythe and Ballard.\n\nBassett's son, [[John F. Bassett]], would follow in his father's path of becoming a professional sports owner; the younger Bassett was a part owner of the [[World Hockey Association]]'s [[Ottawa Nationals]], [[Toronto Toros]] and [[Birmingham Bulls (WHA)|Birmingham Bulls]]; the [[World Football League]]'s [[Memphis Southmen]] and the [[United States Football League]]'s [[Tampa Bay Bandits]].\n\n==Government==\nIn 1989, he was appointed for a three-year term as chairman of the [[Security Intelligence Review Committee]], an independent body that reports to the [[Parliament of Canada]] on the operations of the [[Canadian Security Intelligence Service]]. Due to the requirements under the [[Official Secrets Act]], Bassett was sworn into the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada]].\n\n==Family==\nBassett married fellow [[Bishop's University]] graduate Eleanor Moira Bradley of [[Sherbrooke]] on April 26, 1938 in the University's St. Mark's Chapel.<ref>[http://collections2.banq.qc.ca/jrn03/dn3097/src/1938/04/28/5274927_1938-04-28.txt \"BASSETT-BRADLEY\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625103609/http://collections2.banq.qc.ca/jrn03/dn3097/src/1938/04/28/5274927_1938-04-28.txt |date=2018-06-25 }} ''collections2.banq.qc.ca'' (transcript of the April 28, 1938 ''[[The Record (Sherbrooke)|The Record]]'') June 24, 2018</ref> They had three children: [[John F. Bassett|John]], [[Douglas Bassett (media executive)|Doug]], and David. After their divorce, Bassett married [[Isabel Bassett]] on July 17, 1967.<ref>[http://www.bassettbranches.org/tng/getperson.php?personID=I22&tree=42B \"Isabel Glenthorne Macdonald\"] ''bassettbranches.org'' June 24, 2018</ref> They had three children (Avery, Sarah, and Matthew) and remained together until his death.\n\nIn the 1970s, his son John was the owner of the [[Toronto Toros]], a hockey team in the [[World Hockey Association]]. Former tennis star [[Carling Bassett-Seguso]] is Bassett's granddaughter.\n\n==Honours==\n* 1985 - Made an Officer of the [[Order of Canada]].\n* 1988 - Appointed to the [[Order of Ontario]].\n* 1989 - Appointed to the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada]].\n* 1992 - Promoted to Companion of the Order of Canada.\n* 2000 - Inducted into the [[Canadian Broadcast Hall of Fame]].\n* 2003 - Inducted into the Canadian Business Hall of Fame.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Canadian honour|Type=orc|ID=719|accessdate=24 May 2010}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Conn Smythe]] | title = Principal owner, [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] | years = 1961\u20131970 (with [[Stafford Smythe]] and [[Harold Ballard]]) | after = [[Stafford Smythe]] and [[Harold Ballard]]}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[Ron Atkey]]|\n title=[[Security Intelligence Review Committee|Chair of the Security Intelligence Review Committee (Canada)]]|\n years=1989\u20131992|\n after=[[Jacques Courtois (Canadian)|Jacques Courtois]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{TorontoArgosOwner}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bassett, John}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Anglophone Quebec people]]\n[[Category:Bishop's University alumni]]\n[[Category:Burials at Grove Street Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Canadian Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Canadian mass media owners]]\n[[Category:Canadian military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1945 Canadian federal election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1962 Canadian federal election]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Members of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League executives]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League owners]]\n[[Category:Progressive Conservative Party of Canada candidates for the Canadian House of Commons]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Stanley Cup champions]]\n[[Category:Toronto Maple Leafs executives]]\n[[Category:Toronto Toros]]\n", "name_user": "Blairall", "label": "safe", "comment": "revised a link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Bassett"}
{"title_page": "Marko Ivovi\u0107", "text_new": "{{short description|Serbian volleyball player}}\n{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name           = Marko Ivovi\u0107\n| image          = Marko Ivovic 2014 01.jpg\n| image_size     = <!-- Leave this blank for the default size -->\n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Serbia|Serbian]]\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1990|12|22|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Ljig]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]], [[Serbia]]\n| hometown       = \n| height         = {{height|m=1.92|precision=0}}\n| weight         = {{convert|89|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n| spike          = {{convert|350|cm|abbr=on}}\n| block          = {{convert|330|cm|abbr=on}}\n| college        = \n| position       = Outside hitter\n| currentclub    = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[VC Lokomotiv Novosibirsk|Lokomotiv Novosibirsk]]\n| currentnumber  = 14\n| years          = 2009\u20132012<br>2012\u20132013<br>2013\u20132014<br>2014\u20132015<br>2015\u20132016<br>2016\u20132017<br>2017\u20132018<br>2018\u2013\n| teams          = {{flagicon|SRB}} [[OK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]<br> {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Maliye Milli Piyango SK|Maliye Milli Piyango]]<br> {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Paris Volley]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]<br> {{flagicon|RUS}} [[VC Belogorie|Belogorie Belgorod]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]<br> {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Funvic Taubat\u00e9|V\u00f4lei Taubat\u00e9]]<br> {{flagicon|RUS}} [[VC Lokomotiv Novosibirsk|Lokomotiv Novosibirsk]]\n| nationalyears  = 2012\u2013\n| nationalteam   = {{vb|SRB}}\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men\u2019s [[Volleyball]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Men's European Volleyball Championship|European Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2019 Belgium/France/Netherlands/Slovenia]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2013 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2013 Denmark/Poland]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIVB World League|World League]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|2016 Krak\u00f3w]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|2015 Rio de Janeiro]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Marko Ivovi\u0107''' ({{lang-sr|\u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a\u043e \u0418\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b}}) (born 22 December 1990) is a [[Serbia]]n [[volleyball player]], a member of [[Serbia men's national volleyball team]] and [[Russia|Russian]] club [[VC Lokomotiv Novosibirsk|Lokomotiv Novosibirsk]], bronze medalist of [[2013 Men's European Volleyball Championship|European Championship 2013]], medalist of the [[FIVB World League|World League]], [[PlusLiga|Polish Champion]] ([[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|2015]]).\n\n[[File:Award ceremony 2014 CEV final t224030.jpg|thumb|[[Marko Ivovi\u0107]] poses with the trophy of ''MVP'' and the [[CEV Cup]] after the final of the 2014 CEV Cup in [[Paris]] on March 29, 2014.]]\n\n==Career==\n\n===Clubs===\nIn season 2013/2014 played for [[Paris Volley]]. His team won [[CEV Cup]] and received the ''Most Valuable Player'' title of the final. Ivovi\u0107 was voted the ''Best Player'' of French volleyball league 2013/2014.<ref>[https://www.lequipe.fr/Volley-ball/Actualites/Ivovic-le-volley-dans-le-sang/454344 ''Ivovic : \u00abJ'ai le volley dans le sang\u00bb''] \u2013 lequipe.fr \u2013 04-04-2014</ref> In 2014 he moved to [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]].<ref>[http://www.assecoresovia.pl/pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/art1713,marko-ivovic-nowym-przyjmujacym-asseco-resovii.html ''Marko Ivovi\u0107 nowym przyjmuj\u0105cym Asseco Resovii''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509201458/http://www.assecoresovia.pl/pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/art1713,marko-ivovic-nowym-przyjmujacym-asseco-resovii.html |date=2016-05-09 }} \u2013 assecoresovia.pl \u2013 12-05-2014</ref> In season 2014/2015 he won silver medal of [[2014\u201315 CEV Champions League|CEV Champions League]].<ref>[http://www.assecoresovia.pl/pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/art1992,asseco-resovia-ze-srebrnym-medalem-ligi-mistrzow.html#.VSU2H5Mm-9I ''Asseco Resovia ze srebrnym medalem Ligi Mistrz\u00f3w''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401013116/http://www.assecoresovia.pl/pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/art1992,asseco-resovia-ze-srebrnym-medalem-ligi-mistrzow.html#.VSU2H5Mm-9I |date=2015-04-01 }} \u2013 assecoresovia.pl \u2013 29-03-2015</ref><ref>[http://www.cev.eu/Competition-Area/CompetitionNews.aspx?ID=736&NewsID=19956&TagType=0&TagContent=0&NewsType=0&Paging=0&Sd=1/1/1900&Ed=1/1/1900 ''Three is the magic number for Russian armada from Tatarstan!''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210181047/http://www.cev.eu/Competition-Area/CompetitionNews.aspx?ID=736&NewsID=19956&TagType=0&TagContent=0&NewsType=0&Paging=0&Sd=1%2F1%2F1900&Ed=1%2F1%2F1900 |date=2018-02-10 }} \u2013 cev.eu \u2013 29-03-2015</ref> Then [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]], including Ivovi\u0107, won title of [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Polish Champion 2015]].<ref>[http://www.worldofvolley.com/News/Latest_news/Poland/51403/pol-m-madhouse-in-rzeszw--resovia-is-new-polish-champion.html ''POL M: Madhouse in Rzesz\u00f3w \u2013 Resovia is new Polish champion!''] \u2013 worldofvolley.com \u2013 28-04-2015</ref> In May 2015 he left Polish club and went to Russian [[VC Belogorie|Belogorie Belgorod]]. In April 2016 he came back to [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]].<ref>[http://www.assecoresovia.pl/pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/art2308,marko-ivovic-wraca-do-asseco-resovii.html ''Marko Ivovi\u0107 wraca do Asseco Resovii!''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503045358/http://www.assecoresovia.pl/pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/art2308,marko-ivovic-wraca-do-asseco-resovii.html |date=2016-05-03 }} \u2013 assecoresovia.pl \u2013 29-04-2016</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Russian club [[VC Lokomotiv Novosibirsk|Lokomotiv Novosibirsk]] announced that they had signed Ivovi\u0107 for the 2018-2019 season.<ref>{{cite web |title= Marko Ivovic Leaves Brazil, Signs with Russian Team Lokomotiv |author= Braden Keith |url= https://volleymob.com/marko-ivovic-leaves-brazil-signs-with-russian-team-lokomotiv/ |publisher= VolleyMob |date=2018-05-08|language= English}}</ref>\n\n===National team===\nOn July 19, 2015 [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbian national team]] with him in squad went to the final of [[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|World League]], but they lost to France 0\u20133 and won a silver medal.<ref>[http://worldleague.2015.fivb.com/en/intercontinental-group1/news/france-upset-serbia-to-claim-first-world?id=55058 ''France upset Serbia to claim first World League title''] \u2013 fivb.org \u2013 19-07-2015</ref><ref>[http://worldleague.2015.fivb.com/en/intercontinental-group1/news/france-prevail-over-serbia-to-claim-gold?id=55060 ''France prevail over Serbia to claim gold; USA finish third''] \u2013 fivb.org \u2013 19-07-2015</ref>\n\nOn July 17, 2016, the [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbian national team]] won their first ever [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|World League]] title by a 3-0 win over Brazil. Marko Ivovi\u0107 was pronounced MVP of the final game.<ref>[http://www.fivb.com/en/about/news/serbia-win-first-ever-world-league-title?id=63486 '' MVP performance from Ivovic caps Serbia's success''] \u2013 fivb.org \u2013 17-07-2016</ref><ref>[http://www.fivb.com/en/about/news/mvp-performance-from-ivovic-caps-serbias-success?id=63496 ''Serbia win first ever World League title''] \u2013 fivb.org \u2013 17-07-2016</ref>\n\nMarko Ivovi\u0107 was voted the Best Volleyball Player in Serbia in 2016.<ref>[http://www.rts.rs/page/sport/ci/story/34/odbojka/2572668/boskoviceva-i-ivovic-najbolji-u-2016-godini.html ''\u0411\u043e\u0448\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0435\u0432\u0430 \u0438 \u0418\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b \u043d\u0430\u0458\u0431\u043e\u0459\u0438 \u0443 2016. \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0438''] \u2013 rts.rs \u2013 30-01-2017</ref>\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n====[[CEV Champions League]]====\n* [[File:Silver medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 CEV Champions League|2014/2015]] \u2013 with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n\n====[[CEV Cup]]====\n* [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2013\u201314 Men's CEV Cup|2013/2014]] \u2013 with [[Paris Volley]]\n\n====National championships====\n* '''2009/2010''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Serbian Cup, with [[OK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]\n* '''2010/2011''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Volleyball League of Serbia|Serbian Championship]], with [[OK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]\n* '''2011/2012''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Serbian Cup, with [[OK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]\n* '''2011/2012''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Volleyball League of Serbia|Serbian Championship]], with [[OK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]\n* '''2013/2014''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] French SuperCup, with [[Paris Volley]]\n* '''2013/2014''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Pro A (volleyball)|French Championship]], with [[Paris Volley]]\n* '''2014/2015''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n* '''2015/2016''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Russian Volleyball Super League|Russian Championship]], with [[VC Belogorie|Belogorie Belgorod]]\n* '''2019/2020''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Russian Volleyball Super League|Russian Championship]], with [[VC Lokomotiv Novosibirsk|Lokomotiv Novosibirsk]]\n\n===National team===\n* '''2013''' [[File:Bronze medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2013 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]]\n* '''2015''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n* '''2016''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n* '''2019''' [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2019 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]]\n\n===Individually===\n* '''2014:''' [[Pro A (volleyball)|French Championship]] \u2013 Most Valuable Player\n* '''2014:''' [[Pro A (volleyball)|French Championship]] \u2013 Best Receiver\n* '''2014:''' [[2013\u201314 Men's CEV Cup|CEV Cup]] \u2013 Most Valuable Player\n* '''2016:''' [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]] \u2013 Best Outside Hitter\n* '''2016:''' [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]] \u2013 Most Valuable Player\n* '''2016:''' ''Best Volleyball Player in Serbia''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fivb.org/EN/Volleyball/Competitions/WorldLeague/2010/Players.asp?Tourn=WL2010&Team=SRB&No=132022 FIVB profile]\n* [http://www.plusliga.pl/players/id/26818 PlusLiga player profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box\n| before = {{flagicon|POL}} [[Micha\u0142 Kubiak]]<br /> {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Earvin N'Gapeth]]\n| after = {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Ricardo Lucarelli]]<br /> {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Earvin N'Gapeth]]\n| title = Best Outside Spiker of <br />[[FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n| years = [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|2016]]<br /> <small>ex aequo {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Antonin Rouzier]]</small>\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Earvin N'Gapeth]]\n| after = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Earvin N'Gapeth]]\n| title = Most Valuable Player of <br />[[FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n| years = [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|2016]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{commons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ivovic, Marko}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ljig]]\n[[Category:Serbian men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriates in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in France]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriates in Poland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Poland]]\n[[Category:Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w players]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriates in Russia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Russia]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriates in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Brazil]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Serbian volleyball player}}\n{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name           = Marko Ivovi\u0107\n| image          = Marko Ivovic 2014 01.jpg\n| image_size     = <!-- Leave this blank for the default size -->\n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Serbia|Serbian]]\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1990|12|22|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Ljig]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]], [[Serbia]]\n| hometown       = \n| height         = {{height|m=1.92|precision=0}}\n| weight         = {{convert|89|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n| spike          = {{convert|350|cm|abbr=on}}\n| block          = {{convert|330|cm|abbr=on}}\n| college        = \n| position       = Outside hitter\n| currentclub    = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[VC Lokomotiv Novosibirsk|Lokomotiv Novosibirsk]]\n| currentnumber  = 14\n| years          = 2009\u20132012<br>2012\u20132013<br>2013\u20132014<br>2014\u20132015<br>2015\u20132016<br>2016\u20132017<br>2017\u20132018<br>2018\u2013\n| teams          = {{flagicon|SRB}} [[OK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]<br> {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Maliye Milli Piyango SK|Maliye Milli Piyango]]<br> {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Paris Volley]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]<br> {{flagicon|RUS}} [[VC Belogorie|Belogorie Belgorod]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]<br> {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Funvic Taubat\u00e9]]<br> {{flagicon|RUS}} [[VC Lokomotiv Novosibirsk|Lokomotiv Novosibirsk]]\n| nationalyears  = 2012\u2013\n| nationalteam   = {{vb|SRB}}\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men\u2019s [[Volleyball]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Men's European Volleyball Championship|European Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2019 Belgium/France/Netherlands/Slovenia]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2013 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2013 Denmark/Poland]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIVB World League|World League]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|2016 Krak\u00f3w]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|2015 Rio de Janeiro]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Marko Ivovi\u0107''' ({{lang-sr|\u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a\u043e \u0418\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b}}) (born 22 December 1990) is a [[Serbia]]n [[volleyball player]], a member of [[Serbia men's national volleyball team]] and [[Russia|Russian]] club [[VC Lokomotiv Novosibirsk|Lokomotiv Novosibirsk]], bronze medalist of [[2013 Men's European Volleyball Championship|European Championship 2013]], medalist of the [[FIVB World League|World League]], [[PlusLiga|Polish Champion]] ([[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|2015]]).\n\n[[File:Award ceremony 2014 CEV final t224030.jpg|thumb|[[Marko Ivovi\u0107]] poses with the trophy of ''MVP'' and the [[CEV Cup]] after the final of the 2014 CEV Cup in [[Paris]] on March 29, 2014.]]\n\n==Career==\n\n===Clubs===\nIn season 2013/2014 played for [[Paris Volley]]. His team won [[CEV Cup]] and received the ''Most Valuable Player'' title of the final. Ivovi\u0107 was voted the ''Best Player'' of French volleyball league 2013/2014.<ref>[https://www.lequipe.fr/Volley-ball/Actualites/Ivovic-le-volley-dans-le-sang/454344 ''Ivovic : \u00abJ'ai le volley dans le sang\u00bb''] \u2013 lequipe.fr \u2013 04-04-2014</ref> In 2014 he moved to [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]].<ref>[http://www.assecoresovia.pl/pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/art1713,marko-ivovic-nowym-przyjmujacym-asseco-resovii.html ''Marko Ivovi\u0107 nowym przyjmuj\u0105cym Asseco Resovii''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509201458/http://www.assecoresovia.pl/pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/art1713,marko-ivovic-nowym-przyjmujacym-asseco-resovii.html |date=2016-05-09 }} \u2013 assecoresovia.pl \u2013 12-05-2014</ref> In season 2014/2015 he won silver medal of [[2014\u201315 CEV Champions League|CEV Champions League]].<ref>[http://www.assecoresovia.pl/pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/art1992,asseco-resovia-ze-srebrnym-medalem-ligi-mistrzow.html#.VSU2H5Mm-9I ''Asseco Resovia ze srebrnym medalem Ligi Mistrz\u00f3w''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401013116/http://www.assecoresovia.pl/pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/art1992,asseco-resovia-ze-srebrnym-medalem-ligi-mistrzow.html#.VSU2H5Mm-9I |date=2015-04-01 }} \u2013 assecoresovia.pl \u2013 29-03-2015</ref><ref>[http://www.cev.eu/Competition-Area/CompetitionNews.aspx?ID=736&NewsID=19956&TagType=0&TagContent=0&NewsType=0&Paging=0&Sd=1/1/1900&Ed=1/1/1900 ''Three is the magic number for Russian armada from Tatarstan!''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210181047/http://www.cev.eu/Competition-Area/CompetitionNews.aspx?ID=736&NewsID=19956&TagType=0&TagContent=0&NewsType=0&Paging=0&Sd=1%2F1%2F1900&Ed=1%2F1%2F1900 |date=2018-02-10 }} \u2013 cev.eu \u2013 29-03-2015</ref> Then [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]], including Ivovi\u0107, won title of [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Polish Champion 2015]].<ref>[http://www.worldofvolley.com/News/Latest_news/Poland/51403/pol-m-madhouse-in-rzeszw--resovia-is-new-polish-champion.html ''POL M: Madhouse in Rzesz\u00f3w \u2013 Resovia is new Polish champion!''] \u2013 worldofvolley.com \u2013 28-04-2015</ref> In May 2015 he left Polish club and went to Russian [[VC Belogorie|Belogorie Belgorod]]. In April 2016 he came back to [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]].<ref>[http://www.assecoresovia.pl/pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/art2308,marko-ivovic-wraca-do-asseco-resovii.html ''Marko Ivovi\u0107 wraca do Asseco Resovii!''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503045358/http://www.assecoresovia.pl/pl/aktualnosci/wiadomosci/art2308,marko-ivovic-wraca-do-asseco-resovii.html |date=2016-05-03 }} \u2013 assecoresovia.pl \u2013 29-04-2016</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Russian club [[VC Lokomotiv Novosibirsk|Lokomotiv Novosibirsk]] announced that they had signed Ivovi\u0107 for the 2018-2019 season.<ref>{{cite web |title= Marko Ivovic Leaves Brazil, Signs with Russian Team Lokomotiv |author= Braden Keith |url= https://volleymob.com/marko-ivovic-leaves-brazil-signs-with-russian-team-lokomotiv/ |publisher= VolleyMob |date=2018-05-08|language= English}}</ref>\n\n===National team===\nOn July 19, 2015 [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbian national team]] with him in squad went to the final of [[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|World League]], but they lost to France 0\u20133 and won a silver medal.<ref>[http://worldleague.2015.fivb.com/en/intercontinental-group1/news/france-upset-serbia-to-claim-first-world?id=55058 ''France upset Serbia to claim first World League title''] \u2013 fivb.org \u2013 19-07-2015</ref><ref>[http://worldleague.2015.fivb.com/en/intercontinental-group1/news/france-prevail-over-serbia-to-claim-gold?id=55060 ''France prevail over Serbia to claim gold; USA finish third''] \u2013 fivb.org \u2013 19-07-2015</ref>\n\nOn July 17, 2016, the [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbian national team]] won their first ever [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|World League]] title by a 3-0 win over Brazil. Marko Ivovi\u0107 was pronounced MVP of the final game.<ref>[http://www.fivb.com/en/about/news/serbia-win-first-ever-world-league-title?id=63486 '' MVP performance from Ivovic caps Serbia's success''] \u2013 fivb.org \u2013 17-07-2016</ref><ref>[http://www.fivb.com/en/about/news/mvp-performance-from-ivovic-caps-serbias-success?id=63496 ''Serbia win first ever World League title''] \u2013 fivb.org \u2013 17-07-2016</ref>\n\nMarko Ivovi\u0107 was voted the Best Volleyball Player in Serbia in 2016.<ref>[http://www.rts.rs/page/sport/ci/story/34/odbojka/2572668/boskoviceva-i-ivovic-najbolji-u-2016-godini.html ''\u0411\u043e\u0448\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0435\u0432\u0430 \u0438 \u0418\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b \u043d\u0430\u0458\u0431\u043e\u0459\u0438 \u0443 2016. \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0438''] \u2013 rts.rs \u2013 30-01-2017</ref>\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n====[[CEV Champions League]]====\n* [[File:Silver medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 CEV Champions League|2014/2015]] \u2013 with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n\n====[[CEV Cup]]====\n* [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2013\u201314 Men's CEV Cup|2013/2014]] \u2013 with [[Paris Volley]]\n\n====National championships====\n* '''2009/2010''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Serbian Cup, with [[OK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]\n* '''2010/2011''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Volleyball League of Serbia|Serbian Championship]], with [[OK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]\n* '''2011/2012''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Serbian Cup, with [[OK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]\n* '''2011/2012''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Volleyball League of Serbia|Serbian Championship]], with [[OK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]\n* '''2013/2014''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] French SuperCup, with [[Paris Volley]]\n* '''2013/2014''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Pro A (volleyball)|French Championship]], with [[Paris Volley]]\n* '''2014/2015''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n* '''2015/2016''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Russian Volleyball Super League|Russian Championship]], with [[VC Belogorie|Belogorie Belgorod]]\n* '''2019/2020''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Russian Volleyball Super League|Russian Championship]], with [[VC Lokomotiv Novosibirsk|Lokomotiv Novosibirsk]]\n\n===National team===\n* '''2013''' [[File:Bronze medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2013 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]]\n* '''2015''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n* '''2016''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n* '''2019''' [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2019 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]]\n\n===Individually===\n* '''2014:''' [[Pro A (volleyball)|French Championship]] \u2013 Most Valuable Player\n* '''2014:''' [[Pro A (volleyball)|French Championship]] \u2013 Best Receiver\n* '''2014:''' [[2013\u201314 Men's CEV Cup|CEV Cup]] \u2013 Most Valuable Player\n* '''2016:''' [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]] \u2013 Best Outside Hitter\n* '''2016:''' [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]] \u2013 Most Valuable Player\n* '''2016:''' ''Best Volleyball Player in Serbia''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fivb.org/EN/Volleyball/Competitions/WorldLeague/2010/Players.asp?Tourn=WL2010&Team=SRB&No=132022 FIVB profile]\n* [http://www.plusliga.pl/players/id/26818 PlusLiga player profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box\n| before = {{flagicon|POL}} [[Micha\u0142 Kubiak]]<br /> {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Earvin N'Gapeth]]\n| after = {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Ricardo Lucarelli]]<br /> {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Earvin N'Gapeth]]\n| title = Best Outside Spiker of <br />[[FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n| years = [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|2016]]<br /> <small>ex aequo {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Antonin Rouzier]]</small>\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Earvin N'Gapeth]]\n| after = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Earvin N'Gapeth]]\n| title = Most Valuable Player of <br />[[FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n| years = [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|2016]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{commons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ivovic, Marko}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ljig]]\n[[Category:Serbian men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriates in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in France]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriates in Poland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Poland]]\n[[Category:Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w players]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriates in Russia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Russia]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriates in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Brazil]]\n", "name_user": "Maister1921", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marko_Ivovi%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "R. Austin Freeman", "text_new": "{{other uses|Austin Freeman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n\n'''Richard Austin Freeman''' (11 April 1862 \u2013 28 September 1943) was a British writer of [[detective stories]], mostly featuring the medico-legal [[forensic]] [[detective|investigator]] [[Dr. Thorndyke]]. He claimed to have invented the [[inverted detective story]] (a crime fiction in which the commission of the crime is described at the beginning, usually including the identity of the perpetrator, with the story then describing the detective's attempt to solve the mystery). Freeman used some of his early experiences as a colonial [[surgeon]] in his novels.\n\nMany of the [[Dr. Thorndyke]] stories involve genuine, but often quite arcane, points of scientific knowledge, from areas such as [[tropical medicine]], [[metallurgy]] and [[toxicology]].\n\n==Early life==\nAustin Freeman was the youngest of the five children of tailor Richard Freeman and Ann Maria Dunn.  He first trained as an [[apothecary]] and then studied [[medicine]] at [[Middlesex Hospital]] Medical College, qualifying in 1887.  He specialized in ear, nose, and throat.<ref>Introduction to ''The Best Dr. Thorndyke Detective Stories'' by E. F. Bleiler, Dover edition</ref>  He married Annie Elizabeth the same year, with whom he had two sons.  He was house physician for a short time<ref>Introduction to ''The Best Dr. Thorndyke Detective Stories'' by E. F. Bleiler, Dover edition</ref>, then entered the [[Secretary of State for the Colonies|Colonial Service]] and was sent to [[Accra]] on the [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]] as an assistant surgeon<ref>Introduction to ''The Best Dr. Thorndyke Detective Stories'' by E. F. Bleiler, Dover edition</ref>.\n\n<blockquote>At this time the Gold Coast (present-day Ghana) was a group of semi-independent kingdoms, still unacculturated, subject to incursions by the European colonial powers who were eager to annex them.  The French had been attempting to buy the favor of the native kings, and a British expedition, including Freeman, set out to investigate.  It was mostly through Freeman's intelligence and tact that the expedition was not massacred, and his future seemed assured in the colonial service.<ref>Introduction to ''The Best Dr. Thorndyke Detective Stories'' by E. F. Bleiler, Dover edition</ref></blockquote>\n\nUnfortunately, he contracted [[blackwater fever]] and was sent home.<ref>Author's biography, ''A Silent Witness'', House of Stratus, 2001</ref>\n\n==Career==\nThus, he returned to [[London]] in 1891, serving for a time as acting physician in [[Holloway Prison]]<ref>Author's biography, ''A Silent Witness'', House of Stratus, 2001</ref>, but was unable to find a permanent medical position, so decided to settle down in Gravesend and earn money from writing fiction, while continuing to practice medicine.  His first stories were written in collaboration with [[John James Pitcairn]] (1860\u20131936), medical officer at [[Holloway Prison]], and published under the ''[[nom de plume]]'' \"Clifford Ashdown\".  His first Thorndyke story, ''The Red Thumb Mark'', was published in 1907, and shortly afterwards he pioneered the [[inverted detective story]], in which the identity of the criminal is shown from the beginning.  Some short stories with this feature were collected in ''The Singing Bone'' in 1912.  During [[World War I|the First World War]] he served as a captain in the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]] and afterwards produced a Thorndyke novel almost every year until his death in 1943. The house where he died, 94 Windmill Street in Gravesend, is now Thorndyke's Nursing Home.  [[Norman Donaldson]] wrote a full biography, ''In Search of Dr. Throndyke'', [[Bowling Green University]] Popular Press, Bowling Green, Ohio, 1971.\n\nFreeman claimed to have invented the [[inverted detective story]] in his 1912 collection of short stories ''The Singing Bone''. \"Some years ago I devised, as an experiment, an inverted detective story in two parts.  The first part was a minute and detailed description of a crime, setting forth the antecedents, motives, and all attendant circumstances.  The reader had seen the crime committed, knew all about the criminal, and was in possession of all the facts.  It would have seemed that there was nothing left to tell, but I calculated that the reader would be so occupied with the crime that he would overlook the evidence.  And so it turned out.  The second part, which described the investigation of the crime, had to most readers the effect of new matter.\"<ref>This is a quote from an essay by Freeman entitled \"The Art of the Detective Story\", which is itself quoted in ''The Best Dr. Thorndyke Detective Stories'' (Dover, New York, 1973), in the introduction by E. F. Bleiler.</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nFreeman held conservative political views.<ref name=\"am\">{{cite book |first=Angus |last=McLaren |title=Reproduction by Design: Sex, Robots, Trees, and Test-Tube Babies in Interwar Britain |publisher=University of Chicago Press |year=2012 |isbn=0-226-56069-4 |pages=64\u20135}}</ref> In his 1921 book ''Social Decay and Regeneration'' Freeman put forth the view that [[mechanization]] had flooded Britain with poor-quality goods and created a \"homogenized, restless, unionized working class\".<ref name=\"am\"/> Freeman supported the [[eugenics]] movement and argued that people with \"undesirable\" biological traits should be prevented from breeding through \"segregation, marriage restriction, and\n[[Sterilization (medicine)|sterilization]]\".<ref>McLaren, 2012, (p. 71).</ref> The book also attacked the British [[Labour movement]] and criticised the British government for permitting immigrants (whom Freeman referred to as \"Sub-Man\") to settle in Britain. ''Social Decay and Regeneration'' referred to the [[Russian Revolution]] as \"the Russian catastrophe\" and argued society needed to protected from \"  degenerates of the destructive or \" Bolshevik \" type.\" <ref>R. Austin Freeman, \"Social Decay and Regeneration\", Houghton Mifflin, 1921(p.246).</ref>  Sections of ''Social Decay and Regeneration'' were reprinted in ''[[The Eugenics Review|Eugenics Review]]'', the journal of the British [[Galton Institute|Eugenics Society]].<ref>{{Cite book |first=Dan |last=Stone |title=Breeding Superman: Nietzsche, Race and Eugenics in Edwardian and Interwar Britain |publisher=Liverpool University Press |year=2002 |isbn=0-85323-987-8  |pages=113\u201314, 162}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{too many quotes|section|date=September 2013}}\n\"Indicative of his power is the fact that ''Mr. Polton Explains,'' in some ways his best novel, was written in part in a bomb shelter in 1939, when Freeman was 77 years old. ... For the first twenty-five years of his career, at least, he dominated the world of British detective fiction. ... Freeman was always in the forefront of the form. Today, with [[G. K. Chesterton|Chesterton]], who is remembered for other reasons, he is one of the very few Edwardian detective story writers who are still read.\"<ref name=\"Bleiler\">R. Austin Freeman, ''The Best Dr. Thorndyke Detective Stories'', 1973, Dover (New York), {{ISBN|0-486-20388-3}}, from the introduction by E. F. Bleiler</ref>\n\n\"[[Raymond Chandler]], whose essay '[[The Simple Art of Murder]]' did much toward demolishing the classical detective story, had this to say in a letter to [[Hamish Hamilton]], the British publisher: 'This man Austin Freeman is a wonderful performer.  He has no equal in his genre, and he is also a much better writer than you might think, if you were superficially inclined, because in spite of the immense leisure of his writing, he accomplishes an even suspense which is quite unexpected ... There is even a gaslight charm about his Victorian love affairs, and those wonderful walks across London ...'  Most of us agree with Chandler.\"<ref name=\"Bleiler\" />\n\nIn ''Bloody Murder'', [[Julian Symons]] wrote: \"... [his] talents as a writer were negligible. Reading a Freeman story is very much like chewing dry straw.\"<ref name=\"Symons\">Julian Symons: ''Bloody Murder'', 1972, Faber and Faber (London), {{ISBN|0-571-09465-1}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{wikisource author}}\n* ''Travels and Life in Ashanti and Jaman'' (1898)\n* ''Social Decay and Regeneration'' (1921) (with an introduction by [[Havelock Ellis]])\n\n===Books featuring Dr John Thorndyke===\n[[File:Richard Austin Freeman - L'affare D'Arblay (The D'Arblay Mystery) - I Gialli Mondadori 1931.jpg|thumb|Italian edition of the novel ''The D'Arblay Mystery'' (1926), Mondadori, 1931]]\n\n====Novels====\n* ''The Red Thumb Mark'' (1907)\n* ''The Eye of Osiris'' (1911),  published in the United States as ''The Vanishing Man''\n* ''The Mystery of 31 New Inn'' (1912)\n* ''A Silent Witness'' (1914)\n* ''Helen Vardon's Confession'' (1922)\n* ''The Cat's Eye'' (1923). Serialised, Nottingham Journal (1923)\n* ''The Mystery of Angelina Frood'' (1924)\n* ''The Shadow of the Wolf'' (1925)\n* ''The D'Arblay Mystery'' (1926)\n* ''A Certain Dr. Thorndyke'' (1927)\n* ''As A Thief in the Night'' (1928)\n* ''Mr. Pottermack's Oversight'' (1930)\n* ''Pontifex, Son and Thorndyke'' (1931)\n* ''When Rogues Fall Out'' (1932),  published in the United States as ''Dr. Thorndyke's Discovery''\n* ''Dr. Thorndyke Intervenes'' (1933)\n* ''For the Defence: Dr. Thorndyke'' (1934)\n* ''The Penrose Mystery'' (1936)\n* ''Felo de Se'' (1937),  published in the United States as ''Death At The Inn''\n* ''The Stoneware Monkey'' (1938)\n* ''Mr. Polton Explains'' (1940)\n* ''Dr. Thorndyke's Crime File'' (1941) -- omnibus including \"Meet Dr. Thorndyke\" (essay), ''The Eye of Osiris'' (novel), \"The Art of the Detective Story\" (essay), ''The Mystery of Angelina Frood'' (novel), \"5A King's Bench Walk\" (essay by P. M. Stone), and ''Mr. Pottermack's Oversight'' (novel).\n* ''The Jacob Street Mystery'' (1942),  published in the United States as ''The Unconscious Witness''\n\n====Short-story collections====\n*''John Thorndyke's Cases'' (1909) (published in the United States as ''Dr. Thorndyke's Cases'')\n# The Man with the Nailed Shoes\n# The Stranger's Latchkey\n# The Anthropologist at Large\n# The Blue Sequin\n# The Moabite Cipher\n# The Mandarin's Pearl\n# The Aluminum Dagger\n# A Message from the Deep Sea\n\n*''The Singing Bone'' (1912) (published in the United States as ''The Adventures of Dr. Thorndyke'')\n# The Case of Oscar Broski (an inverted short story)\n##Part I.  The Mechanism of Crime\n##Part II.  The Mechanism of Detection\n# A Case of Premeditation (an inverted short story)\n##Part I.  The Elimination of Mr. Pratt\n##Part II.  Rival Sleuth-Hounds\n# The Echo of a Mutiny (an inverted short story)\n##Part I.  Death on the Sirdler\n##Part II.  \"The Singing Bone\"\n# A Wastrel's Romance (an inverted short story)\n##Part I.  The Spinster's Guest\n##Part II.  Munera Pulveris\n# The Old Lag\n##Part I.  The Changed Immutable\n##Part II.  The Ship of the Desert\n\n*''The Great Portrait Mystery and other Stories'' (1918)\n# The Great Portrait Mystery (not a Thorndyke story)\n# The Bronze Parrot (not a Thorndyke story)\n# The Missing Mortgagee (an inverted Thorndyke short story)\n# Powder Blue and Hawthorne (not a Thorndyke story)\n# Percival Bland's Proxy (an inverted Thorndyke short story)\n# The Attorney's Conscience (not a Thorndyke story)\n# The Luck of Barnabas Mudge (not a Thorndyke story)\n\n*''Dr. Thorndyke's Casebook'' (1923) (published in the United States as ''The Blue Scarab'')\n# The Case of the White Footprints\n# The Blue Scarab\n# The New Jersey Sphinx\n# The Touchstone\n# A Fisher of Men\n# The Stolen Ingots\n# The Funeral Pyre\n*''The Puzzle Lock'' (1925)\n# The Puzzle Lock\n# The Green Check Jacket\n# The Seal of Nebuchadnezzar\n# Phyllis Annesley's Peril\n# A Sower of Pestilence\n# Rex v. Burnaby\n# A Mystery of the Sand-hills\n# The Apparition of Burling Court\n# The Mysterious Visitor\n\n*''The Magic Casket'' (1927)\n# The Magic Casket\n# The Contents of a Mare's Nest\n# The Stalking Horse\n# The Naturalist at Law\n# Mr. Ponting's Alibi\n# Pandora's Box\n# The Trail of Behemoth\n# The Pathologist to the Rescue\n# Gleanings from the Wreckage\n\n* ''The Famous Cases of Dr. Thorndyke'' (London: Hodder & Stoughton, 1929 and later reprintings) -- an omnibus of previously published stories\n# The Case of Oscar Broski (an inverted short story)\n##Part I.  The Mechanism of Crime\n##Part II.  The Mechanism of Detection\n# A Case of Premeditation (an inverted short story)\n##Part I.  The Elimination of Mr. Pratt\n##Part II.  Rival Sleuth-Hounds\n# The Echo of a Mutiny (an inverted short story)\n##Part I.  Death on the Sirdler\n##Part II.  \"The Singing Bone\"\n# A Wastrel's Romance (an inverted short story)\n##Part I.  The Spinster's Guest\n##Part II.  Munera Pulveris\n# The Missing Mortgagee (an inverted Thorndyke short story)\n# Percival Bland's Proxy (an inverted Thorndyke short story)\n# The Old Lag\n##Part I.  The Changed Immutable\n##Part II.  The Ship of the Desert\n# Stranger's Latchkey\n# The Anthropologist at Large\n# The Blue Sequin\n# The Moabite Cipher\n# The Aluminum Dagger\n# The Magic Casket\n# The Contents of a Mare's Nest\n# The Stalking Horse\n# The Naturalist at Law\n# Mr. Ponting's Alibi\n# Pandora's Box\n# The Trail of Behemoth\n# The Pathologist to the Rescue\n# Gleanings from the Wreckage\n# The Puzzle Lock\n# The Green Check Jacket\n# The Seal of Nebuchadnezzar\n# Phyllis Annesley's Peril\n# A Sower of Pestilence\n# Rex v. Burnaby\n# A Mystery of the Sand-hills\n# The Apparition of Burling Court\n# The Mysterious Visitor\n# The Case of the White Footprints\n# The Blue Scarab\n# The New Jersey Sphinx\n# The Touchstone\n# A Fisher of Men\n# The Stolen Ingots\n# The Funeral Pyre\nThe American edition of this is R. Austin Freeman, ''The Dr. Thorndyke Omnibus: 38 of His Criminal Investigations as set down by R. Austin Freeman'' (New York:  Dodd, Mead, 1932 and later reprintings).  The American edition includes one story, \"The Mandarin's Pearl,\" printed in the first Thorndyke short-story collection, ''John Thorndyke's Cases'', but omitted from the British omnibus.  Two other stories, though also appearing in the first Dr. Thorndyke short-story collection, ''John Thorndyke's Cases'', were omitted from the British and American editions of the omnibus collection: \"The Man with the Nailed Shoes\" and \"A Message from the Deep Sea.\"\n\n*''The Best Dr. Thorndyke Detective Stories'' (1973). Edited by E.F. Bleiler. (Includes ''31, New Inn'', believed to have been written between 1905-1911 and later expanded to novel length), which was also published in volume I of the Freeman omnibus, published by [[Battered Silicon Dispatch Box]]\n\n* ''The Dead Hand and Other Uncollected Stories'', edited by [[Douglas G. Greene]] and Tony Medawar  (Shelburne, Ontario: The Battered Silicon Dispatch Box, 1999). (Includes ''The Dead Hand'', believed to have been written in 1912 and later expanded to novel length as ''The Shadow of the Wolf''; the short story was also published in  ''Detection by Gaslight, 14 Victorian detective stories'', an anthology by Douglas G. Greene (Dover. 1997).\n\n===Books featuring Romney Pringle===\n====Books====\n* ''The Adventures of Romney Pringle'', with John Pitcairn, as Clifford Ashdown (1902)\n* ''The Further Adventures of Romney Pringle'', with John Pitcairn, as Clifford Ashdown (1970)<ref>Donaldson, 2nd ed., p.278</ref>\n* ''From a Surgeon's Diary'', with John Pitcairn, as Clifford Ashdown (1977)<ref>Donaldson, 2nd ed., p.280</ref>\n\n====Short stories====\n* \"The Assyrian Rejuvenator\". ''[[Cassell's Magazine]]'', June 1902, reprinted in the ''[[Sheffield Weekly Telegraph]]'', 27 October 1906.  Collected in ''The Adventures of Romney Pringle''.\n* \"The Foreign Office Despatch\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', July 1902. Collected in ''The Adventures of Romney Pringle''\n* \"The Chicago Heiress\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', August 1902. Collected in ''The Adventures of Romney Pringle''\n* \"The Lizard's Scale\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', September 1902. Collected in ''The Adventures of Romney Pringle''\n* \"The Paste Diamonds\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', October 1902. Collected in ''The Adventures of Romney Pringle''\n* \"The Kailyard Novel\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', November 1902. Collected in ''The Adventures of Romney Pringle''\n* \"The Submarine Boat\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', June 1903. Collected in ''The Further Adventures of Romney Pringle''\n* \"The Kimberley Fugitive\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', July 1903. Collected in ''The Further Adventures of Romney Pringle''\n* \"The Silk Worms of Florence\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', August 1903. Collected in ''The Further Adventures of Romney Pringle''\n* \"The Box of Specie\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', September 1903. Collected in ''The Further Adventures of Romney Pringle''\n* \"The Silver Ingots\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', October 1903. Collected in ''The Further Adventures of Romney Pringle''\n* \"The House of Detention\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', November 1903. Collected in ''The Further Adventures of Romney Pringle''\n* \"The Adventure at Heath Crest\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', December 1904. Collected in ''From a Surgeon's Diary''\n* \"How I Acted for an Invalid Doctor\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', January 1905. Collected in ''From a Surgeon's Diary''\n* \"How I Attended a Nervous Patient\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', February 1905. Collected in ''From a Surgeon's Diary''\n* \"How I Met a Very Ignorant Practitioner\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', March 1905. Collected in ''From a Surgeon's Diary''\n* \"How I Cured a Hopeless Paralytic\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', April 1905. Collected in ''From a Surgeon's Diary''\n* \"How I Helped to Lay a Ghost\". ''Cassell's Magazine'', May 1905. Collected in ''From a Surgeon's Diary''\n\n===Other novels and collections===\n* ''The Golden Pool: A Story of a Forgotten Mine'' (1905) <ref>English Catalogue of Books</ref>\n* ''The Unwilling Adventurer'' (1913)\n* ''The Uttermost Farthing'' (1914 in the US, only; first British publication, 1920, as \"A Savant's Vendetta\") <ref>Donaldson, 2nd ed., p.253</ref>\n* ''The Exploits of Danby Croker'' (1916)\n* ''The Surprising Experiences of Mr Shuttlebury Cobb'' (1927) Freeman's original title was ''The Surprising Experiences of Solomon Pike''\n* ''Flighty Phyllis'' (1928)\n* ''The Queen's Treasure'', with John Pitcairn, as  Clifford Ashdown (written around 1905/6, but not published until 1975) <ref>Donaldson, 2nd ed., p. 67 & 279</ref>\n\n====Uncollected short stories====\n* ''The Mutiny on the Speedwell''. Novel Magazine, May 1914 (Jack Osmond). See also A Certain Dr Thorndyke\n* ''The Gun Runner''. Novel Magazine, June 1914 (Jack Osmond). See also A Certain Dr Thorndyke\n\n===Non-fiction===\n* ''The Interior of the Gold Coast''. Macmillan's Magazine, June 1899\n* ''In the London Docks''. Living London, January 1902\n* ''Hospital London''. Living London, June 1902. Reprinted Living London, December 1902\n* ''Afflicted London''. Living London, September 1902. Reprinted Living London, October 1905\n* ''The Coastwise Lights of England''. Cassell's Magazine, November 1902\n* ''London below Bridge''. Living London, December 1902. Reprinted Living London, January 1906\n* ''The Royal Yacht''. Cassell's Magazine, April 1903\n* ''A Thames Sailing Barge Match''. Cassell's Magazine, September 1903\n* ''Small Yacht Racing''. Cassell's Magazine, May 1904\n* ''The Sentinels of the Port of London''. Cassell's Magazine, October 1905\n* ''Down the River''. Cassell's Magazine, January 1906\n* ''The Tightening Grip''. Straits Times, 5 November 1917\n* ''The Art of the Detective Story''. The Nineteenth Century and After, May 1924\n* ''The Pendulum''. Todmorden Advertiser and Hebden Bridge Newsletter, 23 March 1928\n* ''An Englishman's Rights''. Nottingham Evening Post, 28 February 1929 \